IKIDATA}}\n| type = {{#invoke:Wikidata|getValue|P31|FETCH_WIKIDATA}}\n| editor = {{#invoke:Wikidata|getValue|P98|FETCH_WIKIDATA}}\n| owners = {{wikidata|properties|qualifier|qualifier|P127|P580|P582}}\n| publishing_country = {{#invoke:Wikidata|getValue|P495|FETCH_WIKIDATA}}\n| launched = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P577|fetchwikidata=ALL|df=dmy}}\n| foundation = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P577|fetchwikidata=ALL|df=y }}\n| ceased publication = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P2669|fetchwikidata=ALL|df=dmy }}\n| relaunched = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P156|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n| publishing_city = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P291|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n| publisher =  {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P123|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n| circulation = {{#invoke:WikidataIB|getValue|P276|fetchwikidata=ALL}}\n| oclc = {{#invoke:wd|property|P243}}\n}}\n'''The Cardigan Observer''', is a Weekly newspaper published mainly in English . It was circulated generally in the towns and villages of Cardiganshire, Carmarthenshire and Pembrokeshire.<ref name=\":0\">[http://newspapers.library.wales/browse/3015921 The Cardigan Observer] at Welsh Newspapers Online, National Library of Wales</ref>\n\n[[Welsh Newspapers Online]] has digitised 640 issues of the Cardigan Observer (1878-1897) from the newspaper holdings of the [[National Library of Wales]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cardigan Observer}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Wales]]\n\n\n{{UK-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Aivin G.", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Cardigan_Observer"}
{"title_page": "Clara Podda", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Clara Podda\n| nickname = \n| image = Clara Podda.jpg\n| imagesize = 240\n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Italia]]n\n| sport = [[Para table tennis]]\n|disability       = [[Paraplegia]]\n|disability_class = [[Para table tennis#Classification|C2]]\n| event = \n| club = Saint Lucia Sports Club\n| coach = Alessandro Arcigli\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1951|7|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cagliari]], [[Italy]]\n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{ITA}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Table tennis]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{ITA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's team \u2013 Class 1\u20133|Team class 1\u20133]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's individual \u2013 Class 1\u20132|Class 1\u20132]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Table Tennis Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|2010 Gwangju|Team class 1\u20133}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2006 Montreux|Class 1\u20132}}\n}}\n\n'''Clara Podda''' (born 19 July 1951 in [[Cagliari]]) is an Italian [[Paralympic athletics|paralympic athlete]] who has won two medals at the [[Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==Biography==\nMarried with two children, she competed in [[swimming at the 1996 Summer Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=687808&sportid=-1|title=Podda Clara|publisher=paralympic.org|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> She was fourth in the individual [[para table tennis]] tournament in the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]] and also in the [[2004 Summer Paralympics]], before she won her first medals in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Italy at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n*[[Italy at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=clara-podda|old_id=687808}}\n* [http://londra2012.comitatoparalimpico.it/scheda_atleta.php?id=85 Clara Podda] {{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}} at [[Comitato Italiano Paralimpico]] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podda, Clara}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Italian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Italian female table tennis players]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1996 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic table tennis players of Italy]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic medalists in table tennis]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Cagliari]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sardinia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Clara Podda\n| nickname = \n| image = Clara Podda.jpg\n| imagesize = 240\n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Italia]]n\n| sport = [[Para table tennis]]\n|disability       = [[Paraplegia]]\n|disability_class = [[Para table tennis#Classification|C2]]\n| event = \n| club = Saint Lucia Sports Club\n| coach = Alessandro Arcigli\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1951|7|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cagliari]], [[Italy]]\n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{ITA}} \n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Table tennis]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{ITA}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's team \u2013 Class 1\u20133|Team class 1\u20133]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's individual \u2013 Class 1\u20132|Class 1\u20132]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[World Para Table Tennis Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|2010 Gwangju|Team class 1\u20133}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|2006 Montreux|Class 1\u20132}}\n}}\n\n'''Clara Podda''' (born 19 July 1951 in [[Cagliari]]) is an Italian [[Paralympic athletics|paralympic athlete]] who has won two medals at the [[Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==Biography==\nMarried with two children, she competed in [[swimming at the 1996 Summer Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/redirect/ipc.asp?page=athletebio&personid=687808&sportid=-1|title=Podda Clara|publisher=paralympic.org|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> She was fourth in the individual [[para table tennis]] tournament in the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]] and also in the [[2004 Summer Paralympics]], before she won her first medals in the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Italy at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n*[[Italy at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|687808}}\n* [http://londra2012.comitatoparalimpico.it/scheda_atleta.php?id=85 Clara Podda] {{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}} at [[Comitato Italiano Paralimpico]] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podda, Clara}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Italian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Italian female table tennis players]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 1996 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2000 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2004 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic table tennis players of Italy]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Paralympic medalists in table tennis]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:People from Cagliari]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sardinia]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_Podda"}
{"title_page": "Sea of Thieves", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sea of Thieves\n| image =Sea of thieves cover art.jpg\n| caption = Cover art\n| developer = [[Rare (company)|Rare]]\n| publisher = [[Microsoft Studios]]\n| director = [[Gregg Mayles]]\n| producer =  Joe Neate\n| designer = Mike Chapman\n| programmer = Peter Campbell\n| artist = Ryan Stevenson\n| writer = {{ubl|Chris Allcock|Mike Chapman}}\n| composer = [[Robin Beanland]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine 4]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = 20 March 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sea of Thieves''''' is a 2018 [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game developed by [[Rare (company)|Rare]] and published by [[Microsoft Studios]]. In the game, the player assumes the role of a pirates who must complete voyages from different trading companies in order to become the ultimate pirate legends. Played from a [[first-person perspective]], ''Sea of Thieves'' allows a group of players to explore an [[open world]] via a pirate ship, and players must coordinate with each other while they are controlling the ship. The game was described as a \"[[shared world]] adventure game\", which means groups of players will encounter each other regularly throughout their adventures.\n\nNearly all the staff members from Rare worked on the title. The game was inspired by players of [[personal computer|PC]] games such as ''[[Eve Online]]'', ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', who used the tools provided by these games to create their own personal stories. The team considered using other themes such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s before settling on the pirate theme, and the team drew inspirations from titles such as ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]''. The game features a progression system that only unlocks cosmetic items as they wanted to make the title more accessible and encourage players of different experience to play together. Unlike the development of Rare's other games, the development process was transparent, with Rare inviting fans to test the game's early builds.\n\nMicrosoft released the game in March 2018 for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[Xbox One]] and it was released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch. The game received generally mixed reviews upon release, with critics praising the game's ship combat, multiplayer gameplay, visuals and game physics. Criticisms were directed at the game's lack of content, progression and shallow gameplay. Rare envisioned the title as a \"[[game as a service]]\" and released numerous content updates after the game's release. The game was a commercial success, attracting more than 10 million players as of January 2020, prompting Microsoft to declare it the most successful new [[intellectual property]] (IP) they have released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Sea of Thieves gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|In this gameplay screenshot, the player is firing cannonballs at a hostile pirate ship, which is controlled by another group of players.]]\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game played from a [[first-person (video games)|first-person perspective]]. At the beginning of the game, the player selected their player avatar, whose physical appearances and body build are [[procedurally generated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kg5ny/rare-give-me-a-little-control-in-making-my-sea-of-thieves-character|title=Rare, Give Me a Little Control in Making My 'Sea of Thieves' Character|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Vice]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The game is set in a [[shared world]], which means groups of players will encounter each other throughout their adventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jun/22/sea-of-thieves-pirate-adventure-rare-game-developer|title=Sea of Thieves \u2013 the pirate adventure that heralds the return of Rare|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> For solo players, they would sail aboard a [[sloop]] whereas a larger party of players can sail a [[galleon]] cooperatively by assuming different roles such as [[steering]], hoisting sails, navigating using the [[compass]], managing the [[anchor]], and [[navigation|scouting]] via ascending the [[crow's nest]].<ref name=\"sailing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-sailing-terms-sail-into-the-wind-ship-combat-5001|title=Sea of Thieves sailing - how to sail into the wind, win ship combat and sailing terms explained|first=Chris|last=Tapsail|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> in order to control the pirate ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17144806/ships-sloop-galleon-map-barrels-canonballs-bananas-planks-chests-ammo-clothing-vanity-equipment|title=Sea of Thieves ships guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Occasionally players may encounter a hostile group of players who may attack the players' party. Players can fire [[cannonball]]s at the hostile ship using the [[cannon]]s mounted on the ship. Players can also [[Naval boarding|board]] the opponent's ship by shooting themselves out of a cannon or climbing the ship's ladder.<ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/116340/7-more-things-we-want-in-sea-of-thieves|title=7 more things we want in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If areas under the deck takes damage, water will flow in and cause the ship to sink. Players need to patch up the holes with [[Plank (wood)|plank]]s of wood and bail out water using buckets.<ref name=\"sailing\"/> An [[alliance]] can be established with other parties of players. Players in the same alliance receive [[gold]] bonuses should another group completes a voyage. Forming an alliance however does not prevent players from attacking each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/106528/how-to-form-an-alliance-in-sea-of-thieves|title=How to form an alliance in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If the player dies, they would be sent to a [[ghost ship]] named Ferry of the Damned where they would have to wait until they can [[respawn]].<ref name=\"25 tips\"/> A competitive multiplayer mode named Arena was introduced via the ''Anniversary'' update. The gameplay mode sees four teams of players competing against each other to gather silver in a more confined space.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-new-arena-mode-is-all-the-good-and-bad-1834515034|title=Sea of Thieves New Arena Mode Is All The Good (And Bad) Of Sea of Thieves|first=Heather|last=Alexander|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can complete [[quest|voyage]]s from the game's three [[clan (video games)|faction]]s: Gold Hoarders, Order of Souls, and Merchant Alliance. In the quests offered by Gold Hoarders, players are given a [[treasure map]] or a riddle and must locate the treasure. The voyages offered by the Order of Souls are combat challenges, in which players need to collect a magic skull after defeating an enemy [[boss (video games)|boss]]. The quests from Merchant Alliance involves players delivering goods such as live animals to the vendors within a limited time.<ref name=\"factions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17142984/quest-voyage-rank-map-gold-hoarders-order-of-souls-merchant-alliance-rank|title=Sea of Thieves guide to quests and voyages|first=Russ|last=Frushtick|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Upon retrieving the [[Loot box|loot]], they need to deliver them to any representives of the faction, though players holding a treasure chest are defenseless and it can be stolen or taken by other players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-guide-voyages-quests-factions-kraken-skeleton-forts/|title=Sea of Thieves beginner's guide: voyages, factions, and making money|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing voyages would earn the players [[gold]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-how-to-get-started-in-sea-of-thieves-how-to-start-your-first-voyage-controls-explained|title=How to get Started in Sea of Thieves - How to Begin Your First Voyage - Step by Step Guide to Setting Sail, Controls Explained|first=Tom|last=Orry|work=[[USgamer]]|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> which can be spent on buying new customization items or enhancements from vendors in the clothing shops and equipment shops, [[bladesmith|weaponsmith]]s or [[shipbuilding|shipwright]]s.<ref name=\"shops\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143940/shop-vendor-clothing-equipment-weaponsmith-shipwright-trading-companies|title=Sea of Thieves shop guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> A stored named Pirate Emporium was introduced via an update, which allows players to purchase items such as [[pet]]s using [[microtransaction|real-world currency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/09/14/sea-of-thieves-microtransactions/|title=Sea Of Thieves gets a microtransaction store|first=Emily|last=Gera|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=14 September 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can also acquire [[doubloon]]s, which can be traded for gold or reputation, through completing commendations from Blige Rats, the fourth trading company that distributes quests, challenges and cosmetic added via updates or expansions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/sea-of-thieves-guide/2019/5/24/18629418/events-gold-doubloons-bilge-rats-duke-cosmetics|title=Sea of Thieves events and doubloons guide|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Introduced in the ''Anniversary'' update, players can also complete Tall Tales, which is a series of structured narrative missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/13/18617975/sea-of-thieves-tall-tales-review-story-mode-characters|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Tall Tales is the star feature of the anniversary update|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing quests also earned the player reputation points with each factions, which unlock more complicated quests and additional purchasable items.<ref name=\"factions\"/><ref name=\"shops\"/> When the player reaches rank 50 with all the factions and completes all the riddles, they will be inducted as a \"pirate legend\", which grants players new cosmetic items and access to a pirate hideout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-pirate-legend-mysterious-stranger-riddle-solution-rewards-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Pirate Legend and Mysterious Stranger explained - riddle solution, rewards, and how to become Pirate Legend|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can explore the game's [[open world]] together with other players.<ref name=\"exploration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/13/17003856/sea-of-thieves-game-preview|title=Sea of Thieves is huge, fun, and just what the Xbox One needs|first=Tom|last=Warren|work=[[The Verge]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The world is made up of many [[tropical island]]s with varying [[landmass]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-island-map-locations-shapes-names-5001|title=Sea of Thieves map - Island locations, names, shapes and how to find every island|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When exploring the island, players can retrieve items such as [[banana]], which restores the player [[health (game terminology)|health]], wood planks, and cannonballs, while [[ammo]] can be resupplied using the ammo chest in the Captain's Quarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/03/09/sea-of-thieves-open-beta-tips-guide-treasure/|title=Sea of Thieves open beta tips: sailing, treasure, combat and the puke bucket weapon|first=Matt|last=Martin|work=[[VG 247]]|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Weapons including a [[cutlass]], a [[pistol]], a [[blunderbuss]], and a [[sniper rifle]] can be used to defeat hostile enemies like [[skeleton]]s.<ref name=\"25 tips\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-tips/|title=25 essential Sea of Thieves tips to know before you play|first=Sam|last=Loveridge|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\"/> Players can also freely explored the sea, though they may sometimes face adverse weather conditions such as thunderstorms,<ref name=\"sailing\"/> and encounter Skeleton galleons and monsters such as the [[megalodon]] and the [[kraken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/sea-of-thieves-shrouded-spoils-release-date|title=You\u2019ll finally get rewards for killing giant monsters in today\u2019s Sea of Thieves expansion|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>  Additional loot can be discovered through exploring [[shipwreck]]s, and players can also collect and messages hidden in bottles floating in the sea can also be collected.<ref name=\"exploration\"/> Sometimes the players may discover skull clouds, which lead the player to Skeleton Forts, which are [[Raid (military)|raid]]s that can be completed by players in the same server.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-skeleton-forts-skull-clouds-stronghold-keys-fort-assaults-explained-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Skeleton Forts - Skull Clouds, Stronghold Keys and how to defeat the raids|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can interact with other players using [[emotes]] (introduced via an update),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/sea-of-thieves-to-get-pets-emotes-and-new-cosmetics-in-forthcoming-update|title=Sea of Thieves to get pets, emotes and new cosmetics in forthcoming update|first=Imogen|last=Donavan|work=VideoGamer|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> playing [[musical instrument]]s together, and drinking at [[tavern]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/banjo|title=Sea of Thieves is adding banjos to the musical mix|first=Ian|last=Boudrea|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-rare-is-already-immortalising-players-most-memorable-achievements-in-sea-of-thieves-world|title=Rare is already immortalising players' most memorable achievements in Sea of Thieves' world|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and via the ''Anniversary'' update, players can engage in leisure activities such as [[fishing]], hunting, and cooking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was developed by the UK-based developer [[Rare (company)|Rare]]. Rare began conceptualizing the game in 2014 and wanted to create a title where players can create stories together. All of Rare's 200 staff members worked on the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-will-sea-of-thieves-resurrect-rare|title=Sea of Thieves and the Rare revival|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare took five months to created the game's playable prototype named ''Athena'' using [[Unity (engine)|Unity]].<ref name=\"no secret\"/> After playing the prototype, Microsoft's executives including [[Phil Spencer]] and Kudo Tsunoda agreed to [[green-light]] the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/7-things-you-didnt-know-about-sea-of-thieves|title=7 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Sea of Thieves|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-09-sea-of-thieves-early-protoypes-looked-very-different|title=Sea of Thieves' early prototypes looked very different|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare employees also provided the voice for all of the in-game [[non-player character|non-playable character]]s.<ref name=\"voice\"/> ''Sea of Thieves'' also marked Rare's shift from using its own proprietary engine to using [[Unreal Engine 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2018-sea-of-thieves-tech-analysis|title=How Sea of Thieves' tech creates a unique gaming experience|first=John|last=Linneman|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=25 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRare was often considered to be a secretive studio. With ''Sea of Thieves'', a multiplayer-focused game, the studio adopted a more open attitude to its community to ensure that the game's content can resonate with players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/sea-of-thieves-rare-developer-interview-how-players-are-helping-with-design|title=Sea of Thieves is using a unique dev tool: you|first=Stephen|last=Farrelly|work=[[Red Bull]]|date=9 November 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"no secret\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/17/how-rare-cast-away-its-developmental-process-for-sea-of-thieves.aspx|title=How Rare Cast Away Its Developmental Process For Sea Of Thieves|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> The team allowed fans of the game to take part in the game's development by joining the Insider's Program, which allowed players access to an early build of the game. This allowed Rare to experiment with different feature and collected players' feedback. The participants can also discuss with the developers about the game using a pivate forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-22-sea-of-thieves-insider-programme-offers-chance-at-testing-early-builds|title=Sea of Thieves Insider Programme offers chance at testing early builds|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> More than 30,000 players joined the program.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/06/21/how-microsofts-rare-imagined-the-pirate-world-of-sea-of-thieves/|title=How Microsoft\u2019s Rare imagined the pirate world of Sea of Thieves|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Through the Insider's Program, Rare gained more information about how players play the game and interact each other and further helped the team made gameplay decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/sea-thieves-interview-rare-studio-head-craig-duncan-bold-new/|title=Sea of Thieves interview: Rare studio head Craig Duncan on a bold new direction for the legendary British developer |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> For instance, the team decided to include solo play after a lot of players from the Insider's Program had requested it.<ref name=\"solo play\"/>\n\n===Influences and setting===\n{{quotebox|quote=\"I love the idea of things happening in the world that literally can shape the ongoing fabric and lore of ''Sea of Thieves''. The [[Black Beard]] of ''Sea of Thieves'' being a real player in a real crew with a real name - that's really hard to do if you've already painted everyone down a path you want them to go through\"|source= \u2014 Joe Neate, executive producer of Rare<ref name=\"friendliest\"/>|width=33%}}\nStudio director Craig Duncan described the game as the \"friendliest\" multiplayer game.<ref name=\"friendliest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-13-the-sea-of-thieves-endgame-sounds-super-cool|title=The Sea of Thieves endgame sounds super cool|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> While traditionally a console game developer, Rare looked into [[personal computer|PC]] games for inspirations, and realized how players from [[survival game]]s like ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'', ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'' and [[simulation video game|simulation game]]s such as ''[[Eve Online]]'' crafted their own stories using the tools provided by the game. However, Rare remarked that these games are often very punishing in nature. Thus the team wanted to create a similar game that is more light-hearted and accessible for players who are not too fond of multiplayer games.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/sea-of-thieves-return-to-form-for-rare-studi/|title=Who cares about loot? For \u2018Sea of Thieves,\u2019 Rare hid the real fun in the hijinks|first=Will|last=Fulton|work=Digital Trends|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was designed to be a \"light canvass of a world\" where players create their own stories.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> The game did not feature any narrative component at launch because the team felt that by providing structures, players would only be playing an experience that was crafted for them. Joe Neate, the game's executive director, described the game as an \"improv\" comedy, and added that the game is about going \"off-script\".<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> Rare shaped the world and the game's lore to reflect players' action, including various [[Easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s to celebrate their actions or achievements. The team believed that if they include a narrative campaign into the title, incorporating players action into the lore would become very difficult.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> \n\nThe company explored different settings for the game, such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s, though the team eventually settled on the [[piracy|pirate]] theme because it fit with the game's core concept which sees a small group of players cooperating with each other.{{efn|Duncan elaborated that the team was thankful that the team did not chose dinosaur as the setting due to the release of ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' (2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/19/rare-considered-vampire-dinosaur-themes-for-sea-of-thieves-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Considered Vampire, Dinosaur Themes for Sea of Thieves \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Being a pirate also means that players can have a lot of freedom about what they want to do in the game's world and how they want to play the game, and Rare saw the opportunity with the theme as there are not a lot of multiplayer-based pirate games in the market.{{efn|Chapman compared the game to ''[[Red Dead Redemption]]'', which became the default \"[[cowboy]] game\" when it was released in 2010.}} The team looked at various sources for inspirations, including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''. Designer Mike Chapman also believed a lot of parallels can be drawn between ''Sea of Thieves'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'', which is about a group of friends bonding together as they attempt to seek a treasure, and in the process creating a journey that all of them would fondly remember.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Neate added that the game's goal was to evoke \"[a] sense of travel and exploration and discovery\".<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/22/17971710/sea-of-thieves-lore-forsaken-shores-cursed-sails-worldbuilding|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 lore is surprisingly deep, silly and refreshing|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team implemented the \"infinite pirate generator\" instead of allowing players to customize their avatar as they feared that some players would create \"abominations\" that would not have fit the game's visual style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/317084/How_Rare_designed_Sea_of_Thieves_infinite_pirate_generator.php|title=How Rare designed Sea of Thieves' infinite pirate generator|first=Jack|last=Yarwood|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=27 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game features a stylized visual style with hand-painted textures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1025015/Visual-Adventures-on-Sea-of|title=Visual Adventures on 'Sea of Thieves'|work=GDC Vault|first=Ryan|last=Stevenson|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan added that the team chose this painted artstyle because they wanted it to be \"timeless\" and refleccted the game's \"joyful\" and \"delightful\" world.<ref name=\"art\"/>\n\n===Gameplay design===\n\nThe team considered progression-driven experiences as a drawback as this caused experienced players to focus on grinding for endgame content instead of playing with other players, and that novice players may have to worry about their progression lagging significantly behind the more experienced ones. Therefore, the team introduced a \"horizontal\" progression, where players would only earn cosmetic items as they achieve a higher rank. All items have the same attributes, meaning that new players would not be easily margainalized. With the progression system, instead of separating players from each other, more experienced players can assist the novice players to finish the voyages, thus reducing the barrier between the two.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team hoped that this would encourage players to play with each other regardless of their experience and levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-has-fully-embraced-power-levelling-according-to-the-design-director-its-not-what-you-think/|title=Sea of Thieves 'fully embraces' power levelling, according to the design director (it's not what you think)|first=Connor|last=Sheridan|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> As a \"shared world\" adventure game, Rare opted to maintain the distance between each player in a server rather than limiting the number of players a server can accommodate. Chapman believed that this approach can ensure that encountering other players would will be regular but not too frequent.{{efn|Chapman estimated that a player will see another player-controlled ships every 15 minutes to half an hour.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-doesnt-have-a-maximum-or-minimum-server-size|title=Sea of Thieves Has a Very Smart Approach to Server Size|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay was designed to test the player's [[soft skills]]. Players need to exercise their [[common sense]] in order to solve the challenges. For instance, players need to learn to read maps and bail water with buckets. Therefore, the game does not feature a tutorial at launch as the team wanted players to discover the game's mechanics by themselves.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team wanted to give the players tools to play around with, and avoided setting gameplay rules so as to encourage players to utilize their creativity.<ref name=\"solo play\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/when-we-made-sea-of-thieves/|title=When We Made\u2026 Sea of Thieves|first=Marie|last=Dealessandri|work=[[MCVUK]]|date=20 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Despite this, Rare also included [[emergent gameplay]] in a more systemic manner, introducing shipwrecks and fonts that players can discover. Chapman described these locations of interest as the \"catalyst for stories\" which draw different players together, fostering cooperation or competition. Players may sometimes encounter [[sea monster]]s, which is a random incidence that adds a layer of unpredictability to the game.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Due to the game's emergent gameplay, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also considered as a \"watachable and sharable game\", and the team hoped that this will lure players who watched the game on [[video game live streaming|game live streaming]] platforms such as [[twitch (service)|Twitch]] or [[mixer (service)|Mixer]] to purchasing the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\"/>\n\nWhile the game allows solo play, the game is designed to be a multiplayer game where players cooperate with each other. Chapman added that [[cooperative gameplay]] enhances the experience because \"it makes sense in the world\". Players also must coordinate with each other, which makes the experience more \"complex\" and \"rewarding\" for players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/14/sea-of-thieves-lets-you-captain-your-pirate-ship-solo-but-at-a-cost/|title=Sea of Thieves lets you captain your pirate ship solo \u2014 but at a cost|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game does not feature any [[character class]] or specicalization so as to encourage players to adopt different roles instinctively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-01-10-sea-of-thieves-devs-explain-how-its-design-encourages-cooperation|title=Sea of Thieves devs explain how its design encourages cooperation|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The maximum crew size is four as Rare felt that if the group is too large, it does not reflect a sense of \"intimate friendship\" and that some players may sphinter off and make communication between players more difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-dev-explains-why-the-maximum-crew-size-is-4-players|title=Sea of Thieves Dev Explains Why the Maximum Crew Size Is 4 Players|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate described the game as a \"friendship creation tool\" and hoped that the game could become a platform where players can make friends with strangers and bond together.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Rare further added that they felt they have the responsibility to create a \"positive online social space\".<ref name=\"online space\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rare-on-sea-of-thieves-online-we-have-a-responsibility-as-game-creators-to-make-a-positive-social-space/|title=Rare on Sea of Thieves: 'We have a responsibility to make a positive online social space'|first=Joe|last=Donnelly|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Design changes were made to champion the concept of cooperation and friendship. For instance, players cannot hurt others in the same crew,<ref name=\"online space\"/>{{efn|In one of the game's early prototypes, players in the same crew can betray each other, though the feature was scrapped because the team felt that the experience was \"horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/275112/How_emotional_psychology_and_The_Goonies_inspired_Sea_of_Thieves.php?|title=How emotional psychology and The Goonies inspired Sea of Thieves|first=Kris|last=Graft|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=16 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>}} and all rewards are shared equally among crew members.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Neate added that the game provided \"literally no reason or motivation to do anything other that cooperate\".<ref name=\"online space\"/> Rare incorporated several anti-toxicity measures. For instance, players can vote to lock a player into a [[jail cell|brig]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17153164/sea-of-thieves-toxic-brig-scuttle-ship-code-of-conduct|title=Sea of Thieves team put anti-toxicity strategies into game\u2019s core design|first=Julia|last=Alexander|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was announced by publisher [[Xbox Game Studios|Microsoft Studios]] during its press conference at [[E3 2015]], with Duncan describing the game as the \"most ambitious project\" from Rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/rare-announces-most-ambitious-project-yet-sea-of-thieves-294014.phtml|title=Rare announces 'most ambitious project yet,' Sea of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=MacGregor Burleson|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Initially set to be released in 2017, the game was delayed to early 2018 to allow additional development time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2017-sea-of-thieves-delayed-until-2018/1100-6450690/|title=E3 2017: Sea Of Thieves Delayed Until 2018|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft marketed the game extensively.  Players who preordered the game will receive Black Dog Pack, which includes exclusive cosmetic content, and access to a closed [[Software_release_life_cycle#Beta|beta]]. Players can also purchased a separate ''Sea of Thieves''-themed Xbox [[wireless controller]], and anyone who purchased the [[Xbox One X]] console from 18 to 24 March would receive a free digital copy of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/you-can-still-buy-an-xbox-one-x-and-get-sea-of-thi/1100-6457467/|title=You Can Still Buy An Xbox One X And Get Sea Of Thieves Free For A Limited Time|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/17/a-complete-guide-to-sea-of-thievess-preorder-bonuses|title=A Complete Guide to Sea of Thieves' Preorder Bonuses|first=Chris|last=Reed|work=[[IGN]]|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The Australian branch of Microsoft partnered with music band Captain Hellfire & The Wretched Brethren in which the pirate band sang different [[sea shanty|sea chanties]]. The program was braodcasted via [[Facebook]], Mixer and Twitch from 24 to 25 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/xbox-partners-with-an-australian-pirate-band-for-a/1100-6457517/|title=Xbox Partners With An Australian Pirate Band For A Cool Sea Of Thieves Promo|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft also launched \"The Quest\", a global treasure hunt where players need to solve different riddles. The winners would receive one of four golden bananas (each valued at \u00a320,000) as rewards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/10/sea-of-thieves-global-digital-treasure-hunt-features-golden-banana-prize|title=Sea of Thieves Global Digital Treasure Hunt Features Golden Banana Prize|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also hosted a competition which tasked fans to create [[Achievement (video games)|achievement]]s for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-24-can-you-come-up-with-a-sea-of-thieves-achievement|title=Can you come up with a Sea of Thieves Achievement?|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Several [[stress testing (software)|stress test]]s and betas were released for players ahead of the game's official launch on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-09-sea-of-thieves-final-beta-is-here-open-to-everyone-on-xbox-one-and-pc|title=Sea of Thieves' Final Beta is here, open to everyone on Xbox One and PC|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/08/sea-of-thieves-release-date-announced|title=Sea of Thieves Release Date Announced|first=Lucy|last=O'Brien|work=[[IGN]]|date=8 December 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>  At launch, the game suffered from various technical issues, with players reporting not being able to logged into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-issue-status-cinnamonbeard-server-e/1100-6457547/|title=Sea Of Thieves Issue Status: CinnamonBeard Server Error, Not Getting Gold, More|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> According to Duncan, Rare underestimated the server capacity as the number of people logging in to play the game during the launch period was unexpectedly high. Various fixes have since been released to improve the game's online infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-dev-details-how-itll-address-server/1100-6457590/|title=Sea Of Thieves Dev Details How It'll Address Server And Performance Issues|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=23 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a retail release, ''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[Xbox Play Anywhere]] title and the game was made available for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/sea-of-thieves-rare-xbox-one-microsoft|title=Sea of Thieves is Rare\u2019s riskiest voyage yet, but it\u2019s a huge success|first=Matt|last=Kamen|work=[[Wired.co.uk]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-17-these-are-the-first-xbox-play-anywhere-games|title=These are the first Xbox Play Anywhere games|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> However, [[cross-platform play|crossplay]] between PC and Xbox One players was made optional in February 2019 to ensure that all players feel that \"they have a level playing field\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-cross-play-will-be-made-optional-be/1100-6464703/|title=Sea Of Thieves Cross-Play Will Be Made Optional Between Xbox One And PC|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was able to attain a dedicated community following its release despite losing some players after its launch. Players began to set rules, with players developing their own sets of communications and challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/25/17258750/sea-of-thieves-community-rules-agreements-parley|title=Sea of Thieves fans are setting their own rules in the pirate sandbox|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-07-26-meet-the-pirate-who-created-a-racing-league-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Meet the pirate who created a racing league in Sea of Thieves|first=Imogen|last=Beckhelling|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Some also began hosting their own events. To further encourage these players, Rare announced plans to incorporate [[private server]]s into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-will-have-private-servers-to-support-creative-community-events/|title=Sea of Thieves will have private servers to support creative community events|first=Fraser|last=Brown|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nRare envisioned the game to be a \"[[games as a service|game as a service]]\", and expected the game to continue receiving updates for 10 years.<ref name=\"updates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/feb/13/rare-sea-of-thieves-multiplayer-pirates|title=A pirate's life for me: Rare's ambitious plans for Sea of Thieves revealed|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-next-game-you-play-may-never-end/|title=The next big video game you play may never end|first=Ian|last=Sherr|work=[[CNET]]|date=17 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> After the team fixed most of the technical issues, they began looking at players' feedback and identified that one of the major complaints was that there were not enough activities players can participate in the world. Chapman stated that the team's strategy was to give players what they want, ensure that they fit within the ''Sea of Thieves'' universe, and \"surprise\" players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rare-plans-to-give-sea-of-thieves-players-what-the/1100-6460067/|title=Rare Plans To Give Sea Of Thieves Players What They Want|first=Alexandro|last=Fillari|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> For instance, upon listening to fans' negative reaction to \"death cost\", which deducted gold should the player dies, the team scrapped the feature completely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-death-penalty-feature-wont-be-imple/1100-6457714/|title=Sea Of Thieves Death Penalty Feature Won't Be Implemented After All|first=Steve|last=Watts|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare has four teams of employees working in parallel to create the game's various expansions so that large content update can be released frequently and sufficient development time can be given to each team.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/05/01/sea-of-thieves-developer-rare-has-3-teams-making-major-updates/|title=Sea of Thieves developer Rare has 3 teams making major updates|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team hoped to release large content updates every 6 weeks to 2 months, and used \"Bilge Rat Adventures\" which are time-limited challenges to fill the gap between each expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/07/04/rare-on-rpg-elements-battle-royale-potential-and-the-future-of-sea-of-thieves|title=Rare On RPG Elements, Battle Royale Potential, And The Future Of Sea Of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=Hilliard|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ultimate goal was to make the game \"as big and successful as it can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/22/rare-studio-head-on-sea-of-thieves-post-launch-plans-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Studio Head on Sea of Thieves Post-Launch Plans \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The first major expansion, ''The Hungering Deep'', was developed within 2 months. The second expansion, ''Cursed Sails'', introduced skeleton ships controlled by [[artificial intelligence]] (AI). Despite being adamant about not doing so prior to the game's launch, the team decided to implement the feature nonetheless as this was among one of the biggest fan requests.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/> The ''Anniversary'' update which adds both Tall Tales and the Arena mode was so massive that it was described as a \"relaunch\" for the game.<ref name=\"second launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-04-10-the-second-launch-of-sea-of-thieves|title=The second launch of Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> All the additional content are free of charge as they did not want to divide the player base.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-08-06-keeping-sea-of-thieves-afloat|title=Keeping Sea of Thieves afloat|first=James|last=Batchelor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=7 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Major expansion packs\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:16%;\"| Release date\n! style=\"width:70%;\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''The Hungering Deep''\n| 20 May 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-17-sea-of-thieves-first-proper-content-update-the-hungering-deep-gets-a-teaser-trailer|title=Sea of Thieves' first proper content update, The Hungering Deep, gets a teaser trailer|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ''The Hungering Deep'' introduced new tools such as the Speaking trumphet and a narrative campaign featuring the [[megalodon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-sea-of-thieves-hungering-deep-guide/megalodon-shark-guide|title=Sea of Thieves Megalodon Guide - How to Find the Megalogon, How to Defeat the Hungering One|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Cursed Sails''\n| 31 July 2018<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\"/>\n| ''Cursed Sails'' introduced AI ship, a new story campaign, the [[brigantine]] which can accmmodate three players, and the \"alliance\" mechanic.<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-cursed-sails-update-now-live-4-things-you-need-to-know/|title=Sea of Thieves' Cursed Sails update now live - 4 things you need to know|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Forsaken Shores''\n| 27 September 2018\n| ''Forsaken Shores'' introduced new cosmetic items, a new volanic region named Devil's Roar, a new type of voyage named \"Cargo Run\", a [[rowboat]], a narrative campaign centered on Forsaken Shores Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-25-heres-everything-happening-in-this-weeks-sea-of-thieves-forsaken-shores-update|title=Here's everything happening in this week's Sea of Thieves Forsaken Shores update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Shrouded Spoils''\n| 28 November 2018\n| ''Shrouded Spoils'' introduced [[fog]] into the game. The update also changed the AI behavior of both the kraken and the megalodon, and altered some of the existing gameplay systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-28-sea-of-thieves-big-shrouded-spoils-update-is-here-and-the-waters-never-been-deadlier|title=Sea of Thieves' big Shrouded Spoils update is here, and the water's never been deadlier|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Anniversary''\n| 30 April 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/111488/what-time-does-the-sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-start|title=What time does the Sea of Thieves Anniversary Update start?|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The ''Anniversary'' update introduced a separate player-versus-player (PvP) competitive multiplayer mode named ''Arena'', the first narrative-based Tall Tales campaign named ''Shores of Gold'' which consists of nine chapters, and the ''Hunter's Call'', which added fishing, cooking and hunting into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update/|title=Sea of Thieves' anniversary update finally makes the game reach its full potential|first=Samuel|last=Roberts|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Black Powder Staches''\n| 17 July 2019\n| ''Black Power Staches'' includes a series of missions that task players to collect gunpowder barrels and then sold them to various factions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-black-powder-stashes-update-is-live/|title=Sea of Thieves' Black Powder Stashes update is live|first=Christopher|last=Livington|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dark Relics''\n| 15 August 2019\n| ''Dark Relics'' introduces new voyages, cosmetic items, new commentations, and rowboats mounted with [[harpoon gun]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-dark-relics-update-is-here-with-new-voyages/|title=Sea of Thieves' Dark Relics update is here with new voyages|first=Jordan|last=Gerblick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Smuggler's Fortune''\n| 11 September 2019\n| The update introduces Pirate Emporium, a new store that supports [[microtransaction]]s. A new type of currency named \"Ancient Coins\" can be purchased from Xbox store, though they can also be earned in the game. Players can also buy [[monkey]]s and [[parrot]]s as pets from Pirate Emporium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/11/20860753/sea-of-thieves-smugglers-fortune-update-pets|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Smuggler\u2019s Fortune update is now live, and it adds pets|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Fort of the Damned''\n| 16 October 2019\n| ''Fort of the Damned'' introduced several [[Halloween]]-themed cosmetics, a new skeleton font, and a new type of enemy named Shadow Skeletons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-gets-spooky-with-new-fort-of-the-da/1100-6470608/|title=Sea Of Thieves Gets Spooky With New Fort Of The Damned Update|first=Jordan|last=Ramee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Seabound Soul''\n| 20 November 2019\n| ''The Seabound Soul'' introduced fire into the game with the fiery cannonball and a new Tall Tales which sees players partnering with adventurer Sir Arthur Pendragon as they embarck on a journey to seek a \"feared ship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-the-seabound-soul-update-now-live/1100-6471606/|title=Sea Of Thieves' The Seabound Soul Update Now Live|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Festival of Giving''\n| 11 December 2019\n| ''Festival of Giving'' introduced several [[Christmas]]-themed cosmetic items and a mission that task the players to assist Stitcher Jim to collect a shipment of gifts that was lost to the sea. A new tutorial mode named Maiden Voyage was also added into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-holiday-event-adds-gift-seeker-voyages-and-tutorial-mode/|title=Sea of Thieves' holiday event adds Gift Seeker Voyages and tutorial mode|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Legends of the Sea''\n| 15 January 2020\n| ''Legends of the Sea'' celebrated the game's most notable players by tasking players to embarck on a quest to seek various easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/legends-of-the-sea-release-date|title=Sea of Thieves: Legends of the Sea makes you part of the lore|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Crews of Rage''\n| 19 February 2020\n| ''Crews of Rage'' brought players back to Devil's Roar where they need to complete Bounty Voyages, which involves the acquisition of a new chest named the Chest of Rage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2020/02/19/crews-of-rage-sea-of-thieves-free-update-released/|title=The latest free update to Sea of Thieves is Crews of Rage|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|work=[[VG 247]]|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Heart of Fire''\n| 11 March 2020\n| ''Heart of Fire'' introduced the chain-shot and the blunderbomb, a throwable explosive, and included more Tall Tales missions which continue the story started in ''The Seabound Soul''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-04-sea-of-thieves-enters-the-trap-laden-heart-of-fire-in-next-weeks-big-update|title=Sea of Thieves enters the trap-laden Heart of Fire in next week's big update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' saw frequent collaborations with other Microsoft franchises. The Bird and Bear Figurehead, based on Rare's own ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]'' series, was released in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/05/sea-of-thieves-new-item-is-a-lovely-banjo-kazooie-reference|title=Sea of Thieves: New Item Is a Lovely Banjo-Kazooie Reference|first=Alex|last=Gilyadov|work=[[IGN]]|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Ships based on the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' series and the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise were released in June and November 2019 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/10/halo-spartan-ship-set-announced-for-sea-of-thieves-e3-2019|title=Halo Spartan Ship Set Announced for Sea of Thieves - E3 2019|first=Colin|last=Stevens|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-is-giving-away-a-gears-of-war-inspired-ship-set-for-a-week/|title=Sea of Thieves is giving away a Gears of War-inspired ship set for a week|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also expanded ''Sea of Thieves'' to other mediums. It have partnered with [[Mongoose Publishing]] to release a [[tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] game titled ''Sea of Thieves Roleplaying Game'' in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-31-theres-a-sea-of-thieves-tabletop-rpg-on-the-way|title=There's a Sea of Thieves tabletop RPG on the way|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Comics]] debuted a comic series in March 2018, with [[Jeremy Whitley]] being the writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-comic-series-announced-check-out-so/1100-6455724/|title=Sea Of Thieves Comic Series Announced, Check Out Some Art|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Books]] also worked with Rare to publish an art-book named ''Tales from the Sea of Thieves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/xbox/2018/3/20/17140292/sea-of-thieves-lore-artbook-preview-tales-from-the-sea-of-thieves-book|title=Tales From the Sea of Thieves is a deep dive into a pirate lore ocean|first=Susana|last=Polo|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 66/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><br>(XONE) 69/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 6.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web |last=Devore |first=Jordan |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sea-of-thieves-495603.phtml |title=Review: Sea of Thieves |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| EuroG = Recommended<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-27-sea-of-thieves-review|title=Sea of Thieves review|first=Christian|last=Donlan|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web |last=Hilliard |first=Kyle |date=23 March 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sea_of_thieves/b/xboxone/archive/2018/03/23/game-informer-sea-of-thieves-xbox-one-review.aspx |title=Fun In A Shallow Pool - Sea of Thieves - Xbox One |work=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Tamburro |first=Paul |date=26 March 2018 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/377727-sea-of-thieves-review-rarely-exciting-xbox-one |title=Sea of Thieves Review \u2013 Rarely Exciting (Xbox One) |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref name=\"GSpotRev\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=27 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sea-of-thieves-review-set-sail-with-trepidation/1900-6416887/ |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web |last=Loveridge |first=Sam |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review: Doesn\u2019t have the (sea)legs for longevity |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8/10 (2020)<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Jagneaux|first=David |date= 20 March 2020 |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-review-2020 |title=Sea of Thieves Review (2020) |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate= 25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| Poly = 6.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=Frushtick |first=Russ |date=22 March 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17151248/sea-of-thieves-review-xbox-one-pc |title=Sea of Thieves review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 72/100<ref name=\"PCGRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Wilde |first=Tyler |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-pc-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews from critics, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> Most critics agreed that the game has potential and a good foundation but lamented that the game suffered from a lack of content and doubted Rare's decision to release ''Sea of Thieves'' as a full-priced game.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The game's graphics and the [[game physics]] for the sea also received acclaim from critics.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> \n\nThe multiplayer portion of the game received acclaim. Jordan Devore from ''[[Destructoid]]'' noted that with a full crew, the game could get chaotic and situations could turn volatile very quickly. He added that cooperation with strangers can also be deeply satisfying and added that these moments can create unforgettable experiences for players.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Peter Brown from ''[[GameSpot]]'' also enjoyed coordinating with other players or simply goofing around, though he remarked that some players were [[trolling]] others and caused the experience to become frustrating.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Jeff Grubb from ''[[VentureBeat]]'' also enjoyed the game, saying that playing with strangers often created numerous hilarious moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/03/20/sea-of-thieves-is-mesmerizing-and-hilarious/|title=Sea of Thieves is mesmerizing and hilarious|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Kyle Hilliard from ''[[Game Informer]]'' stated that each session \"results in a story\" due to the emergent gameplay, and praised Rare for successfully creating an excellent \"pirate simulator\" and \"manufacturing a digital playground that is fun to explore\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/>  Sam Loveridge from ''[[GamesRadar]]'' likewise commented that the game is \"an anecdote generator at its very best\" due to its emergent storytelling.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Brandin Tyrrel from ''[[IGN]]'' stated that \"''Sea of Thieves'' works well when treated like a [[chat room]] or a [[party game]], where it serves as catalyst for having a good time with the people you\u2019re with\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Tyrell |first=Brandin |date=27 March 2018 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/sea-of-thieves-review |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay received generally negative reviews. Devore felt that the quests were repetitive and that the world did not have a lot of interesting things to do.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Paul Tamburro from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' agreed, remarking that the quests had little variety and did not allow room for creativity. While he praised the huge [[sandbox game|sandbox]], he felt that there were not enough secrets or stories players can discover in the world.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Loverdige called the voyages \"elaborated [[fetch quest]]s. He lamented that there were no option to turn off PvP in the game and that they cannot customize their own characters.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Russ Frushtick from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' remarked that misbehaving players can make the experience frustrating because PvP can never be disabled. However, he remarked that the game offered no incentive for players who wanted to engage in PvP combat.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Hilliard felt that the game did not have enough content to keep players engaged, and remarked that the combat felt bland. Many critics commented that players would not be motivated to complete quests because only cosmetic items are unlocked.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/> Tyrrel praised the ship combat, though he felt that the respawn system was too forgiving.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Christian Donlan from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' likewise called the ship combat \"thrilling\" and the general combat \"crunchy, pleasantly basic\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Tyler Wilde from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' liked exploring the shipwrecks for evoking a sense of discovery, though he commented that he wished more emergent events would happen in the ocean.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Solo play received mixed opinions. Some critics thought that it was more difficult,<ref name=\"polysolo\"/> boring,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-is-no-fun-by-yourself-1823934837|title=Sea Of Thieves Is No Fun By Yourself|first=Mike|last=Fahey|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and maddening,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/03/21/sea-of-thieves-solo-play/|title=Sea of Thieves solo is maddening and brutal - as it should be|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while some remarked that it is entertaining,<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> satisfying,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\"/> and relaxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-01-why-i-love-sailing-alone-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Why I love sailing alone in Sea of Thieves|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"polysolo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17150830/playing-sea-of-thieves-solo-experience|title=The case for sailing solo in Sea of Thieves|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing a year of updates, the game received a more positive reception from critics. Following the ''Anniversary'' update, ''IGN'' stated that players should give the game a second chance and that it was the \"perfect time\" for players to return to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/why-now-is-a-great-time-to-return-to-sea-of-thieves|title=Why Now Is a Great Time to Return to Sea of Thieves|first=Mark|last=Merlinda|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Nicole Carpenter from ''Polygon'' praised the post-launch updates for making the title more \"curated\" with more structure and direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> David Jagneaux from ''IGN'', in his re-review of the game in 2020, praised the Tall Tales and its riddles, which he described as \"brain teasers that really challenge [player's] detective skills\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> In his summary, he wrote that the game is a \"pirate fantasy sandbox with an enormous amount of things to do, made unpredictable and exciting by the addition of other players\".<ref name = \"IGN\"/> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' named ''Sea of Thieves'' the Best Ongoing Game of 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/best-ongoing-game-2019-sea-of-thieves/|title=Best Ongoing Game 2019: Sea of Thieves|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while Gameindustry.biz declared the title one of their [[Game of the Year|Games of the Year]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-15-game-of-the-year-2019-sea-of-thieves|title=Games of the Year 2019: Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Sea of Thieves'' was a commercial success. The title attracted more than 1 million players two days after it has released,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-seeing-unprecedented-demand-passes-/1100-6457743/|title=Sea Of Thieves Seeing \"Unprecedented\" Demand, Passes 1 Million Players|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> It was the best-selling retail game in the UK in its week of release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-26-sea-of-thieves-lands-uk-chart-number-one|title=Sea of Thieves lands UK chart number one|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and it became the second best-selling game in the US in March 2018, only behind ''[[Far Cry 5]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/far-cry-5-sea-of-thieves-march-npd/|title=Far Cry 5 and Sea of Thieves best-selling games in US during March, according to NPD|first=James|last=Billcliffe|work=[[VG 247]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2018, Microsoft declared the game as the fast-selling new IP released for the Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-microsofts-fastest-selling-new-i/1100-6457750/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Microsoft's Fastest-Selling New IP On Xbox One|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-11-quantum-break-uks-best-selling-boxed-game |title=Quantum Break UK's best-selling boxed game |first=Wesley |last=Yin-Poole |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Rare attributed the game's success to the title releasing for Xbox Game Pass subscribers at launch, which enabled the game to achieved Rare's sales target for three months in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-06-18-sea-of-thieves-hit-three-month-target-in-a-single-day|title=Sea of Thieves hit three month target in a single day|first=Matthew|last= Handrahan|work=[[Gameindustry.biz]]|date=18 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Game Pass contributed to half of the sales of ''Sea of Thieves'',<ref name=\"second launch\"/> though Microsoft added that the game sold well without counting the Game Pass sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/315909/Microsoft_says_Sea_of_Thieves_sold_well_even_without_counting_Game_Pass_copies.php|title=Microsoft says Sea of Thieves sold well, even without counting Game Pass copies|first=Alissa|last=McAloon|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game passed five million players in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-08-01-sea-of-thieves-sloops-past-5m-players|title=Sea of Thieves passes 5m players|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Microsoft declared the game the most successful IP it has released in the generation, with the game amassing more than 10 million players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-now-xboxs-most-successful-new-ip/1100-6472598/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Now Xbox's \"Most Successful\" New IP Of The Generation|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In addition to good sales, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also popular with viewers, with the title being ranked as one of the most watched titles on Twitch in January 2019 following the ''Shrouded Spoils'' update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-has-unexpectedly-become-one-of-twitchs-b-1831997645|title=Sea Of Thieves Has Unexpectedly Become One Of Twitch's Biggest Games|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=23 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/22/18193421/sea-of-thieves-twitch-ninja-dr-disrespect-summit1g|title=Sea of Thieves is enjoying a resurgence on Twitch|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2016\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2016nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2016 (2016 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Gamescom]] 2016\n| Best Xbox One Game\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamelibrarian.com/best-of-gamescom-2016-winners-selected-by-gamescom-committee/|title=Best of Gamescom 2016 Winners Selected by Gamescom Committee|publisher=The Video Game Librarian|date=19 August 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Online Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/golden-joystick-awards/news/a807943/golden-joystick-awards-2016-voting-now-open-to-the-public/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2016 voting now open to the public|website=[[Digital Spy]]|author=Sam Loveridge|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Game Critics Awards\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2017nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2017 (2017 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://bestinslot.co/golden-joystick-awards-2017-nominees/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2017 Nominees|publisher=Best in Slot|first=Eri|last=Gaito|date=13 November 2017|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"16\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Develop (magazine)|Develop Awards]]\n| Animation\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/announcing-the-develop-awards-2018-nominations-shortlist|title=Announcing the Develop Awards 2018 nominations shortlist|magazine=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]|author=MCV staff|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Music Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Sound Design \n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Gameplay Innovation\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[The Independent Game Developers' Association]] Awards 2018\n| Best Action and Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2018-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2018 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2018|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/awards/2018-winners|title=2018 Winners|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|date=1 November 2018|accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Creativity Award\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Visual Design\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Audio Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/news/golden-joysticks-2018-nominees-announced-voting-open-now/|title=Golden Joysticks 2018 nominees announced, voting open now|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Tom Hoggins|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=6 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/golden-joystick-awards-2018-winners/|title=Golden Joystick Awards 2018 winners: God of War wins big but Fortnite gets Victory Royale|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|author=Connor Sheridan|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Co-operative Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Xbox Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[The Game Awards 2018]]\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/game-awards-tga/2018/12/6/18130000/the-game-awards-winners-2018|title=The Game Awards 2018: Here are all the winners|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|author=Christopher Grant|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]]\n| Best Artistic Design\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|title=Titanium Awards 2018|website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]]|accessdate=7 November 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707230958/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|archivedate=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-12-10-red-dead-redemption-2-wins-best-game-at-fun-and-serious-festival-awards|title=Red Dead Redemption 2 wins Best Game at Fun & Serious Festival Awards|website=GamesIndustry.biz|author=Matthew Handrahan|date=10 December 2018|accessdate=7 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Family Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Australian Games Awards\n| Multiplayer/Online Title of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.australiangamesawards.com/news/|title=Your 2018 Winners|publisher=Australian Games Awards|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"9\" | 2019\n| [[D.I.C.E. Awards]]\n| Online Game of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/god-of-war-spider-man-lead-dice-awards-heres-all-t/1100-6464345/|title=God Of War, Spider-Man Lead DICE Awards; Here's All The Nominees|website=[[GameSpot]]|author=Eddie Makuch|date=10 January 2019|accessdate=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[NAVGTR Awards]]\n| Design, New IP\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://navgtr.org/archives/3566/|title=Nominee List for 2018|publisher=[[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Game, Original Action\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[15th British Academy Games Awards]]\n| Evolving Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/gaming/news/british-academy-games-awards-2019-nominees-1203163369/|title=\u2018God of War,\u2019 \u2018Red Dead 2\u2019 Lead BAFTA Game Awards Nominations|author=Stefanie Fogel|date=14 March 2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Italian Video Game Awards\n| Innovation Award\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://italianvideogameawards.com/awards|title=Italian Video Game Awards Nominees and Winners|website=Italian Video Game Awards|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ivor Novello Awards]]\n| Best Original Video Game Score\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8513011/2019-ivor-novello-awards-winners-list|title=Mariah Carey and The 1975 Win 2019 Ivor Novello Awards|author=Gil Kaufman|date=24 May 2019|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| The Independent Game Developers' Association Awards 2019\n| Best Social Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tiga.org/news/tiga-announces-games-industry-awards-2019-finalists|title=TIGA Announces Games Industry Awards 2019 Finalists|publisher=[[The Independent Game Developers' Association]]|author=Suzi Stephenson|date=19 September 2019|accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Golden Joystick Awards\n| Best Game Expansion (''Anniversary Update'')\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|author=Stephen Tailby|date=20 September 2019|website=Push Square|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.seaofthieves.com/}}\n\n{{Rare}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kraken in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Microsoft games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer vehicle operation games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Persistent worlds]]\n[[Category:Rare (company) games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Video games about pirates]]\n[[Category:Video games with downloadable content]]\n[[Category:Video games with cross-platform play]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Robin Beanland]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring protagonists of selectable gender]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Xbox Play Anywhere games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Sea of Thieves\n| image =Sea of thieves cover art.jpg\n| caption = Cover art\n| developer = [[Rare (company)|Rare]]\n| publisher = [[Microsoft Studios]]\n| director = [[Gregg Mayles]]\n| producer =  Joe Neate\n| designer = Mike Chapman\n| programmer = Peter Campbell\n| artist = Ryan Stevenson\n| writer = {{ubl|Chris Allcock|Mike Chapman}}\n| composer = [[Robin Beanland]]\n| engine = [[Unreal Engine 4]]\n| platforms = {{ubl|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = 20 March 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Sea of Thieves''''' is a 2018 [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game developed by [[Rare (company)|Rare]] and published by [[Microsoft Studios]]. In the game, the player assumes the role of a pirates who must complete voyages from different trading companies in order to become the ultimate pirate legends. Played from a [[first-person perspective]], ''Sea of Thieves'' allows a group of players to explore an [[open world]] via a pirate ship, and players must coordinate with each other while they are controlling the ship. The game was described as a \"[[shared world]] adventure game\", which means groups of players will encounter each other regularly throughout their adventures.\n\nNearly all the staff members from Rare worked on the title. The game was inspired by players of [[personal computer|PC]] games such as ''[[Eve Online]]'', ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'', who used the tools provided by these games to create their own personal stories. The team considered using other themes such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s before settling on the pirate theme, and the team drew inspirations from titles such as ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[The Goonies]]''. The game features a progression system that only unlocks cosmetic items as they wanted to make the title more accessible and encourage players of different experience to play together. Unlike the development of Rare's other games, the development process was transparent, with Rare inviting fans to test the game's early builds.\n\nMicrosoft released the game in March 2018 for [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] and [[Xbox One]] and it was released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch. The game received generally mixed reviews upon release, with critics praising the game's ship combat, multiplayer gameplay, visuals and game physics. Criticisms were directed at the game's lack of content, progression and shallow gameplay. Rare envisioned the title as a \"[[game as a service]]\" and released numerous content updates after the game's release. The game was a commercial success, attracting more than 10 million players as of January 2020, prompting Microsoft to declare it the most successful new [[intellectual property]] (IP) they have released in the [[Eighth generation of video game consoles|generation]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Sea of Thieves gameplay screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|In this gameplay screenshot, the player is firing cannonballs at a hostile pirate ship, which is controlled by another group of players.]]\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] video game played from a [[first-person (video games)|first-person perspective]]. At the beginning of the game, the player selected their player avatar, whose physical appearances and body build are [[procedurally generated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kg5ny/rare-give-me-a-little-control-in-making-my-sea-of-thieves-character|title=Rare, Give Me a Little Control in Making My 'Sea of Thieves' Character|first=Austin|last=Walker|work=[[Vice]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The game is set in a [[shared world]], which means groups of players will encounter each other throughout their adventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/jun/22/sea-of-thieves-pirate-adventure-rare-game-developer|title=Sea of Thieves \u2013 the pirate adventure that heralds the return of Rare|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> For solo players, they would sail aboard a [[sloop]] whereas a larger party of players can sail a [[galleon]] cooperatively by assuming different roles such as [[steering]], hoisting sails, navigating using the [[compass]], managing the [[anchor]], and [[navigation|scouting]] via ascending the [[crow's nest]].<ref name=\"sailing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-sailing-terms-sail-into-the-wind-ship-combat-5001|title=Sea of Thieves sailing - how to sail into the wind, win ship combat and sailing terms explained|first=Chris|last=Tapsail|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> in order to control the pirate ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17144806/ships-sloop-galleon-map-barrels-canonballs-bananas-planks-chests-ammo-clothing-vanity-equipment|title=Sea of Thieves ships guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Occasionally players may encounter a hostile group of players who may attack the players' party. Players can fire [[cannonball]]s at the hostile ship using the [[cannon]]s mounted on the ship. Players can also [[Naval boarding|board]] the opponent's ship by shooting themselves out of a cannon or climbing the ship's ladder.<ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/116340/7-more-things-we-want-in-sea-of-thieves|title=7 more things we want in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If areas under the deck takes damage, water will flow in and cause the ship to sink. Players need to patch up the holes with [[Plank (wood)|plank]]s of wood and bail out water using buckets.<ref name=\"sailing\"/> An [[alliance]] can be established with other parties of players. Players in the same alliance receive [[gold]] bonuses should another group completes a voyage. Forming an alliance however does not prevent players from attacking each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/106528/how-to-form-an-alliance-in-sea-of-thieves|title=How to form an alliance in Sea of Thieves|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=3 August 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> If the player dies, they would be sent to a [[ghost ship]] named Ferry of the Damned where they would have to wait until they can [[respawn]].<ref name=\"25 tips\"/> A competitive multiplayer mode named Arena was introduced via the ''Anniversary'' update. The gameplay mode sees four teams of players competing against each other to gather silver in a more confined space.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-new-arena-mode-is-all-the-good-and-bad-1834515034|title=Sea of Thieves New Arena Mode Is All The Good (And Bad) Of Sea of Thieves|first=Heather|last=Alexander|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can complete [[quest|voyage]]s from the game's three [[clan (video games)|faction]]s: Gold Hoarders, Order of Souls, and Merchant Alliance. In the quests offered by Gold Hoarders, players are given a [[treasure map]] or a riddle and must locate the treasure. The voyages offered by the Order of Souls are combat challenges, in which players need to collect a magic skull after defeating an enemy [[boss (video games)|boss]]. The quests from Merchant Alliance involves players delivering goods such as live animals to the vendors within a limited time.<ref name=\"factions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17142984/quest-voyage-rank-map-gold-hoarders-order-of-souls-merchant-alliance-rank|title=Sea of Thieves guide to quests and voyages|first=Russ|last=Frushtick|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Upon retrieving the [[Loot box|loot]], they need to deliver them to any representives of the faction, though players holding a treasure chest are defenseless and it can be stolen or taken by other players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-guide-voyages-quests-factions-kraken-skeleton-forts/|title=Sea of Thieves beginner's guide: voyages, factions, and making money|first=Tyler|last=Wilde|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing voyages would earn the players [[gold]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-how-to-get-started-in-sea-of-thieves-how-to-start-your-first-voyage-controls-explained|title=How to get Started in Sea of Thieves - How to Begin Your First Voyage - Step by Step Guide to Setting Sail, Controls Explained|first=Tom|last=Orry|work=[[USgamer]]|date=17 January 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> which can be spent on buying new customization items or enhancements from vendors in the clothing shops and equipment shops, [[bladesmith|weaponsmith]]s or [[shipbuilding|shipwright]]s.<ref name=\"shops\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/20/17143940/shop-vendor-clothing-equipment-weaponsmith-shipwright-trading-companies|title=Sea of Thieves shop guide|first=Jeffery|last=Parkin|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> A stored named Pirate Emporium was introduced via an update, which allows players to purchase items such as [[pet]]s using [[microtransaction|real-world currency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/09/14/sea-of-thieves-microtransactions/|title=Sea Of Thieves gets a microtransaction store|first=Emily|last=Gera|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=14 September 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can also acquire [[doubloon]]s, which can be traded for gold or reputation, through completing commendations from Blige Rats, the fourth trading company that distributes quests, challenges and cosmetic added via updates or expansions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/sea-of-thieves-guide/2019/5/24/18629418/events-gold-doubloons-bilge-rats-duke-cosmetics|title=Sea of Thieves events and doubloons guide|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=24 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Introduced in the ''Anniversary'' update, players can also complete Tall Tales, which is a series of structured narrative missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/13/18617975/sea-of-thieves-tall-tales-review-story-mode-characters|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Tall Tales is the star feature of the anniversary update|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Completing quests also earned the player reputation points with each factions, which unlock more complicated quests and additional purchasable items.<ref name=\"factions\"/><ref name=\"shops\"/> When the player reaches rank 50 with all the factions and completes all the riddles, they will be inducted as a \"pirate legend\", which grants players new cosmetic items and access to a pirate hideout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-pirate-legend-mysterious-stranger-riddle-solution-rewards-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Pirate Legend and Mysterious Stranger explained - riddle solution, rewards, and how to become Pirate Legend|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers can explore the game's [[open world]] together with other players.<ref name=\"exploration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/13/17003856/sea-of-thieves-game-preview|title=Sea of Thieves is huge, fun, and just what the Xbox One needs|first=Tom|last=Warren|work=[[The Verge]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The world is made up of many [[tropical island]]s with varying [[landmass]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-island-map-locations-shapes-names-5001|title=Sea of Thieves map - Island locations, names, shapes and how to find every island|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> When exploring the island, players can retrieve items such as [[banana]], which restores the player [[health (game terminology)|health]], wood planks, and cannonballs, while [[ammo]] can be resupplied using the ammo chest in the Captain's Quarters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/03/09/sea-of-thieves-open-beta-tips-guide-treasure/|title=Sea of Thieves open beta tips: sailing, treasure, combat and the puke bucket weapon|first=Matt|last=Martin|work=[[VG 247]]|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Weapons including a [[cutlass]], a [[pistol]], a [[blunderbuss]], and a [[sniper rifle]] can be used to defeat hostile enemies like [[skeleton]]s.<ref name=\"25 tips\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-tips/|title=25 essential Sea of Thieves tips to know before you play|first=Sam|last=Loveridge|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shacknews 7 more things\"/> Players can also freely explored the sea, though they may sometimes face adverse weather conditions such as thunderstorms,<ref name=\"sailing\"/> and encounter Skeleton galleons and monsters such as the [[megalodon]] and the [[kraken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/sea-of-thieves-shrouded-spoils-release-date|title=You\u2019ll finally get rewards for killing giant monsters in today\u2019s Sea of Thieves expansion|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>  Additional loot can be discovered through exploring [[shipwreck]]s, and players can also collect and messages hidden in bottles floating in the sea can also be collected.<ref name=\"exploration\"/> Sometimes the players may discover skull clouds, which lead the player to Skeleton Forts, which are [[Raid (military)|raid]]s that can be completed by players in the same server.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-03-sea-of-thieves-skeleton-forts-skull-clouds-stronghold-keys-fort-assaults-explained-5001|title=Sea of Thieves Skeleton Forts - Skull Clouds, Stronghold Keys and how to defeat the raids|first=Chris|last=Tapsell|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=3 April 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Players can interact with other players using [[emotes]] (introduced via an update),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/sea-of-thieves-to-get-pets-emotes-and-new-cosmetics-in-forthcoming-update|title=Sea of Thieves to get pets, emotes and new cosmetics in forthcoming update|first=Imogen|last=Donavan|work=VideoGamer|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> playing [[musical instrument]]s together, and drinking at [[tavern]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/banjo|title=Sea of Thieves is adding banjos to the musical mix|first=Ian|last=Boudrea|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-rare-is-already-immortalising-players-most-memorable-achievements-in-sea-of-thieves-world|title=Rare is already immortalising players' most memorable achievements in Sea of Thieves' world|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and via the ''Anniversary'' update, players can engage in leisure activities such as [[fishing]], hunting, and cooking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was developed by the UK-based developer [[Rare (company)|Rare]]. Rare began conceptualizing the game in 2014 and wanted to create a title where players can create stories together. All of Rare's 200 staff members worked on the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-26-will-sea-of-thieves-resurrect-rare|title=Sea of Thieves and the Rare revival|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare took five months to created the game's playable prototype named ''Athena'' using [[Unity (engine)|Unity]].<ref name=\"no secret\"/> After playing the prototype, Microsoft's executives including [[Phil Spencer]] and Kudo Tsunoda agreed to [[green-light]] the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/7-things-you-didnt-know-about-sea-of-thieves|title=7 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Sea of Thieves|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=14 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-04-09-sea-of-thieves-early-protoypes-looked-very-different|title=Sea of Thieves' early prototypes looked very different|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare employees also provided the voice for all of the in-game [[non-player character|non-playable character]]s.<ref name=\"voice\"/> ''Sea of Thieves'' also marked Rare's shift from using its own proprietary engine to using [[Unreal Engine 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2018-sea-of-thieves-tech-analysis|title=How Sea of Thieves' tech creates a unique gaming experience|first=John|last=Linneman|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=25 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRare was often considered to be a secretive studio. With ''Sea of Thieves'', a multiplayer-focused game, the studio adopted a more open attitude to its community to ensure that the game's content can resonate with players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/au-en/sea-of-thieves-rare-developer-interview-how-players-are-helping-with-design|title=Sea of Thieves is using a unique dev tool: you|first=Stephen|last=Farrelly|work=[[Red Bull]]|date=9 November 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"no secret\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/11/17/how-rare-cast-away-its-developmental-process-for-sea-of-thieves.aspx|title=How Rare Cast Away Its Developmental Process For Sea Of Thieves|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=17 November 2017|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> The team allowed fans of the game to take part in the game's development by joining the Insider's Program, which allowed players access to an early build of the game. This allowed Rare to experiment with different feature and collected players' feedback. The participants can also discuss with the developers about the game using a pivate forum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-11-22-sea-of-thieves-insider-programme-offers-chance-at-testing-early-builds|title=Sea of Thieves Insider Programme offers chance at testing early builds|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=22 November 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> More than 30,000 players joined the program.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/06/21/how-microsofts-rare-imagined-the-pirate-world-of-sea-of-thieves/|title=How Microsoft\u2019s Rare imagined the pirate world of Sea of Thieves|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Through the Insider's Program, Rare gained more information about how players play the game and interact each other and further helped the team made gameplay decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/features/sea-thieves-interview-rare-studio-head-craig-duncan-bold-new/|title=Sea of Thieves interview: Rare studio head Craig Duncan on a bold new direction for the legendary British developer |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> For instance, the team decided to include solo play after a lot of players from the Insider's Program had requested it.<ref name=\"solo play\"/>\n\n===Influences and setting===\n{{quotebox|quote=\"I love the idea of things happening in the world that literally can shape the ongoing fabric and lore of ''Sea of Thieves''. The [[Black Beard]] of ''Sea of Thieves'' being a real player in a real crew with a real name - that's really hard to do if you've already painted everyone down a path you want them to go through\"|source= \u2014 Joe Neate, executive producer of Rare<ref name=\"friendliest\"/>|width=33%}}\nStudio director Craig Duncan described the game as the \"friendliest\" multiplayer game.<ref name=\"friendliest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-13-the-sea-of-thieves-endgame-sounds-super-cool|title=The Sea of Thieves endgame sounds super cool|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> While traditionally a console game developer, Rare looked into [[personal computer|PC]] games for inspirations, and realized how players from [[survival game]]s like ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'', ''[[Rust (video game)|Rust]]'' and [[simulation video game|simulation game]]s such as ''[[Eve Online]]'' crafted their own stories using the tools provided by the game. However, Rare remarked that these games are often very punishing in nature. Thus the team wanted to create a similar game that is more light-hearted and accessible for players who are not too fond of multiplayer games.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/sea-of-thieves-return-to-form-for-rare-studi/|title=Who cares about loot? For \u2018Sea of Thieves,\u2019 Rare hid the real fun in the hijinks|first=Will|last=Fulton|work=Digital Trends|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was designed to be a \"light canvass of a world\" where players create their own stories.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> The game did not feature any narrative component at launch because the team felt that by providing structures, players would only be playing an experience that was crafted for them. Joe Neate, the game's executive director, described the game as an \"improv\" comedy, and added that the game is about going \"off-script\".<ref name=\"friendliest\"/> Rare shaped the world and the game's lore to reflect players' action, including various [[Easter egg (media)|easter egg]]s to celebrate their actions or achievements. The team believed that if they include a narrative campaign into the title, incorporating players action into the lore would become very difficult.<ref name=\"friendliest\"/><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> \n\nThe company explored different settings for the game, such as [[vampire]]s and [[dinosaur]]s, though the team eventually settled on the [[piracy|pirate]] theme because it fit with the game's core concept which sees a small group of players cooperating with each other.{{efn|Duncan elaborated that the team was thankful that the team did not chose dinosaur as the setting due to the release of ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]'' (2017)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/19/rare-considered-vampire-dinosaur-themes-for-sea-of-thieves-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Considered Vampire, Dinosaur Themes for Sea of Thieves \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Being a pirate also means that players can have a lot of freedom about what they want to do in the game's world and how they want to play the game, and Rare saw the opportunity with the theme as there are not a lot of multiplayer-based pirate games in the market.{{efn|Chapman compared the game to ''[[Red Dead Redemption]]'', which became the default \"[[cowboy]] game\" when it was released in 2010.}} The team looked at various sources for inspirations, including ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' and ''[[Black Sails (TV series)|Black Sails]]''. Designer Mike Chapman also believed a lot of parallels can be drawn between ''Sea of Thieves'' and ''[[The Goonies]]'', which is about a group of friends bonding together as they attempt to seek a treasure, and in the process creating a journey that all of them would fondly remember.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Neate added that the game's goal was to evoke \"[a] sense of travel and exploration and discovery\".<ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/10/22/17971710/sea-of-thieves-lore-forsaken-shores-cursed-sails-worldbuilding|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 lore is surprisingly deep, silly and refreshing|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team implemented the \"infinite pirate generator\" instead of allowing players to customize their avatar as they feared that some players would create \"abominations\" that would not have fit the game's visual style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/317084/How_Rare_designed_Sea_of_Thieves_infinite_pirate_generator.php|title=How Rare designed Sea of Thieves' infinite pirate generator|first=Jack|last=Yarwood|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=27 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game features a stylized visual style with hand-painted textures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1025015/Visual-Adventures-on-Sea-of|title=Visual Adventures on 'Sea of Thieves'|work=GDC Vault|first=Ryan|last=Stevenson|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Duncan added that the team chose this painted artstyle because they wanted it to be \"timeless\" and refleccted the game's \"joyful\" and \"delightful\" world.<ref name=\"art\"/>\n\n===Gameplay design===\n\nThe team considered progression-driven experiences as a drawback as this caused experienced players to focus on grinding for endgame content instead of playing with other players, and that novice players may have to worry about their progression lagging significantly behind the more experienced ones. Therefore, the team introduced a \"horizontal\" progression, where players would only earn cosmetic items as they achieve a higher rank. All items have the same attributes, meaning that new players would not be easily margainalized. With the progression system, instead of separating players from each other, more experienced players can assist the novice players to finish the voyages, thus reducing the barrier between the two.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team hoped that this would encourage players to play with each other regardless of their experience and levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-has-fully-embraced-power-levelling-according-to-the-design-director-its-not-what-you-think/|title=Sea of Thieves 'fully embraces' power levelling, according to the design director (it's not what you think)|first=Connor|last=Sheridan|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> As a \"shared world\" adventure game, Rare opted to maintain the distance between each player in a server rather than limiting the number of players a server can accommodate. Chapman believed that this approach can ensure that encountering other players would will be regular but not too frequent.{{efn|Chapman estimated that a player will see another player-controlled ships every 15 minutes to half an hour.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-doesnt-have-a-maximum-or-minimum-server-size|title=Sea of Thieves Has a Very Smart Approach to Server Size|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe gameplay was designed to test the player's [[soft skills]]. Players need to exercise their [[common sense]] in order to solve the challenges. For instance, players need to learn to read maps and bail water with buckets. Therefore, the game does not feature a tutorial at launch as the team wanted players to discover the game's mechanics by themselves.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> The team wanted to give the players tools to play around with, and avoided setting gameplay rules so as to encourage players to utilize their creativity.<ref name=\"solo play\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development-news/when-we-made-sea-of-thieves/|title=When We Made\u2026 Sea of Thieves|first=Marie|last=Dealessandri|work=[[MCVUK]]|date=20 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Despite this, Rare also included [[emergent gameplay]] in a more systemic manner, introducing shipwrecks and fonts that players can discover. Chapman described these locations of interest as the \"catalyst for stories\" which draw different players together, fostering cooperation or competition. Players may sometimes encounter [[sea monster]]s, which is a random incidence that adds a layer of unpredictability to the game.<ref name=\"DigitalTrend making\"/> Due to the game's emergent gameplay, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also considered as a \"watachable and sharable game\", and the team hoped that this will lure players who watched the game on [[video game live streaming|game live streaming]] platforms such as [[twitch (service)|Twitch]] or [[mixer (service)|Mixer]] to purchasing the game.<ref name=\"Watchable game\"/>\n\nWhile the game allows solo play, the game is designed to be a multiplayer game where players cooperate with each other. Chapman added that [[cooperative gameplay]] enhances the experience because \"it makes sense in the world\". Players also must coordinate with each other, which makes the experience more \"complex\" and \"rewarding\" for players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/06/14/sea-of-thieves-lets-you-captain-your-pirate-ship-solo-but-at-a-cost/|title=Sea of Thieves lets you captain your pirate ship solo \u2014 but at a cost|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=14 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game does not feature any [[character class]] or specicalization so as to encourage players to adopt different roles instinctively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2017-01-10-sea-of-thieves-devs-explain-how-its-design-encourages-cooperation|title=Sea of Thieves devs explain how its design encourages cooperation|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=11 January 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The maximum crew size is four as Rare felt that if the group is too large, it does not reflect a sense of \"intimate friendship\" and that some players may sphinter off and make communication between players more difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/13/sea-of-thieves-dev-explains-why-the-maximum-crew-size-is-4-players|title=Sea of Thieves Dev Explains Why the Maximum Crew Size Is 4 Players|first=Joe|last=Skrebels|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Neate described the game as a \"friendship creation tool\" and hoped that the game could become a platform where players can make friends with strangers and bond together.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Rare further added that they felt they have the responsibility to create a \"positive online social space\".<ref name=\"online space\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rare-on-sea-of-thieves-online-we-have-a-responsibility-as-game-creators-to-make-a-positive-social-space/|title=Rare on Sea of Thieves: 'We have a responsibility to make a positive online social space'|first=Joe|last=Donnelly|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Design changes were made to champion the concept of cooperation and friendship. For instance, players cannot hurt others in the same crew,<ref name=\"online space\"/>{{efn|In one of the game's early prototypes, players in the same crew can betray each other, though the feature was scrapped because the team felt that the experience was \"horrible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/275112/How_emotional_psychology_and_The_Goonies_inspired_Sea_of_Thieves.php?|title=How emotional psychology and The Goonies inspired Sea of Thieves|first=Kris|last=Graft|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=16 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>}} and all rewards are shared equally among crew members.<ref name=\"no secret\"/> Neate added that the game provided \"literally no reason or motivation to do anything other that cooperate\".<ref name=\"online space\"/> Rare incorporated several anti-toxicity measures. For instance, players can vote to lock a player into a [[jail cell|brig]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17153164/sea-of-thieves-toxic-brig-scuttle-ship-code-of-conduct|title=Sea of Thieves team put anti-toxicity strategies into game\u2019s core design|first=Julia|last=Alexander|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Sea of Thieves'' was announced by publisher [[Xbox Game Studios|Microsoft Studios]] during its press conference at [[E3 2015]], with Duncan describing the game as the \"most ambitious project\" from Rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/rare-announces-most-ambitious-project-yet-sea-of-thieves-294014.phtml|title=Rare announces 'most ambitious project yet,' Sea of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=MacGregor Burleson|work=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 June 2015|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Initially set to be released in 2017, the game was delayed to early 2018 to allow additional development time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2017-sea-of-thieves-delayed-until-2018/1100-6450690/|title=E3 2017: Sea Of Thieves Delayed Until 2018|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft marketed the game extensively.  Players who preordered the game will receive Black Dog Pack, which includes exclusive cosmetic content, and access to a closed [[Software_release_life_cycle#Beta|beta]]. Players can also purchased a separate ''Sea of Thieves''-themed Xbox [[wireless controller]], and anyone who purchased the [[Xbox One X]] console from 18 to 24 March would receive a free digital copy of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/you-can-still-buy-an-xbox-one-x-and-get-sea-of-thi/1100-6457467/|title=You Can Still Buy An Xbox One X And Get Sea Of Thieves Free For A Limited Time|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/17/a-complete-guide-to-sea-of-thievess-preorder-bonuses|title=A Complete Guide to Sea of Thieves' Preorder Bonuses|first=Chris|last=Reed|work=[[IGN]]|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The Australian branch of Microsoft partnered with music band Captain Hellfire & The Wretched Brethren in which the pirate band sang different [[sea shanty|sea chanties]]. The program was braodcasted via [[Facebook]], Mixer and Twitch from 24 to 25 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/xbox-partners-with-an-australian-pirate-band-for-a/1100-6457517/|title=Xbox Partners With An Australian Pirate Band For A Cool Sea Of Thieves Promo|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Microsoft also launched \"The Quest\", a global treasure hunt where players need to solve different riddles. The winners would receive one of four golden bananas (each valued at \u00a320,000) as rewards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/10/sea-of-thieves-global-digital-treasure-hunt-features-golden-banana-prize|title=Sea of Thieves Global Digital Treasure Hunt Features Golden Banana Prize|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also hosted a competition which tasked fans to create [[Achievement (video games)|achievement]]s for the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-01-24-can-you-come-up-with-a-sea-of-thieves-achievement|title=Can you come up with a Sea of Thieves Achievement?|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=24 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Several [[stress testing (software)|stress test]]s and betas were released for players ahead of the game's official launch on 17 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-09-sea-of-thieves-final-beta-is-here-open-to-everyone-on-xbox-one-and-pc|title=Sea of Thieves' Final Beta is here, open to everyone on Xbox One and PC|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/12/08/sea-of-thieves-release-date-announced|title=Sea of Thieves Release Date Announced|first=Lucy|last=O'Brien|work=[[IGN]]|date=8 December 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>  At launch, the game suffered from various technical issues, with players reporting not being able to logged into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-issue-status-cinnamonbeard-server-e/1100-6457547/|title=Sea Of Thieves Issue Status: CinnamonBeard Server Error, Not Getting Gold, More|first=Chris|last=Pereira|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> According to Duncan, Rare underestimated the server capacity as the number of people logging in to play the game during the launch period was unexpectedly high. Various fixes have since been released to improve the game's online infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-dev-details-how-itll-address-server/1100-6457590/|title=Sea Of Thieves Dev Details How It'll Address Server And Performance Issues|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=23 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a retail release, ''Sea of Thieves'' is an [[Xbox Play Anywhere]] title and the game was made available for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/sea-of-thieves-rare-xbox-one-microsoft|title=Sea of Thieves is Rare\u2019s riskiest voyage yet, but it\u2019s a huge success|first=Matt|last=Kamen|work=[[Wired.co.uk]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-06-17-these-are-the-first-xbox-play-anywhere-games|title=These are the first Xbox Play Anywhere games|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=17 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> However, [[cross-platform play|crossplay]] between PC and Xbox One players was made optional in February 2019 to ensure that all players feel that \"they have a level playing field\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-cross-play-will-be-made-optional-be/1100-6464703/|title=Sea Of Thieves Cross-Play Will Be Made Optional Between Xbox One And PC|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=4 February 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''Sea of Thieves'' was able to attain a dedicated community following its release despite losing some players after its launch. Players began to set rules, with players developing their own sets of communications and challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/25/17258750/sea-of-thieves-community-rules-agreements-parley|title=Sea of Thieves fans are setting their own rules in the pirate sandbox|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-07-26-meet-the-pirate-who-created-a-racing-league-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Meet the pirate who created a racing league in Sea of Thieves|first=Imogen|last=Beckhelling|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Some also began hosting their own events. To further encourage these players, Rare announced plans to incorporate [[private server]]s into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-will-have-private-servers-to-support-creative-community-events/|title=Sea of Thieves will have private servers to support creative community events|first=Fraser|last=Brown|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nRare envisioned the game to be a \"[[games as a service|game as a service]]\", and expected the game to continue receiving updates for 10 years.<ref name=\"updates\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2018/feb/13/rare-sea-of-thieves-multiplayer-pirates|title=A pirate's life for me: Rare's ambitious plans for Sea of Thieves revealed|first=Keith|last=Stuart|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=13 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-next-game-you-play-may-never-end/|title=The next big video game you play may never end|first=Ian|last=Sherr|work=[[CNET]]|date=17 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> After the team fixed most of the technical issues, they began looking at players' feedback and identified that one of the major complaints was that there were not enough activities players can participate in the world. Chapman stated that the team's strategy was to give players what they want, ensure that they fit within the ''Sea of Thieves'' universe, and \"surprise\" players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/rare-plans-to-give-sea-of-thieves-players-what-the/1100-6460067/|title=Rare Plans To Give Sea Of Thieves Players What They Want|first=Alexandro|last=Fillari|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> For instance, upon listening to fans' negative reaction to \"death cost\", which deducted gold should the player dies, the team scrapped the feature completely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-death-penalty-feature-wont-be-imple/1100-6457714/|title=Sea Of Thieves Death Penalty Feature Won't Be Implemented After All|first=Steve|last=Watts|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare has four teams of employees working in parallel to create the game's various expansions so that large content update can be released frequently and sufficient development time can be given to each team.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/05/01/sea-of-thieves-developer-rare-has-3-teams-making-major-updates/|title=Sea of Thieves developer Rare has 3 teams making major updates|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The team hoped to release large content updates every 6 weeks to 2 months, and used \"Bilge Rat Adventures\" which are time-limited challenges to fill the gap between each expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/interview/2018/07/04/rare-on-rpg-elements-battle-royale-potential-and-the-future-of-sea-of-thieves|title=Rare On RPG Elements, Battle Royale Potential, And The Future Of Sea Of Thieves|first=Kyle|last=Hilliard|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=4 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The ultimate goal was to make the game \"as big and successful as it can be\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/22/rare-studio-head-on-sea-of-thieves-post-launch-plans-a-ign-unfiltered|title=Rare Studio Head on Sea of Thieves Post-Launch Plans \u2014 IGN Unfiltered|first=Alex|last=Osborn|work=[[IGN]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The first major expansion, ''The Hungering Deep'', was developed within 2 months. The second expansion, ''Cursed Sails'', introduced skeleton ships controlled by [[artificial intelligence]] (AI). Despite being adamant about not doing so prior to the game's launch, the team decided to implement the feature nonetheless as this was among one of the biggest fan requests.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\"/> The ''Anniversary'' update which adds both Tall Tales and the Arena mode was so massive that it was described as a \"relaunch\" for the game.<ref name=\"second launch\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-04-10-the-second-launch-of-sea-of-thieves|title=The second launch of Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> All the additional content are free of charge as they did not want to divide the player base.<ref name=\"keeping it afloat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-08-06-keeping-sea-of-thieves-afloat|title=Keeping Sea of Thieves afloat|first=James|last=Batchelor|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=7 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 | Major expansion packs\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:16%;\"| Release date\n! style=\"width:70%;\"| Notes\n|-\n| ''The Hungering Deep''\n| 20 May 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-17-sea-of-thieves-first-proper-content-update-the-hungering-deep-gets-a-teaser-trailer|title=Sea of Thieves' first proper content update, The Hungering Deep, gets a teaser trailer|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| ''The Hungering Deep'' introduced new tools such as the Speaking trumphet and a narrative campaign featuring the [[megalodon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/01-08-2018-sea-of-thieves-hungering-deep-guide/megalodon-shark-guide|title=Sea of Thieves Megalodon Guide - How to Find the Megalogon, How to Defeat the Hungering One|first=Hirun|last=Cryer|work=[[USgamer]]|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Cursed Sails''\n| 31 July 2018<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\"/>\n| ''Cursed Sails'' introduced AI ship, a new story campaign, the [[brigantine]] which can accmmodate three players, and the \"alliance\" mechanic.<ref name=\"Cursed Sails\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-cursed-sails-update-now-live-4-things-you-need-to-know/|title=Sea of Thieves' Cursed Sails update now live - 4 things you need to know|first=Sam|last=Prell|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Forsaken Shores''\n| 27 September 2018\n| ''Forsaken Shores'' introduced new cosmetic items, a new volanic region named Devil's Roar, a new type of voyage named \"Cargo Run\", a [[rowboat]], a narrative campaign centered on Forsaken Shores Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-25-heres-everything-happening-in-this-weeks-sea-of-thieves-forsaken-shores-update|title=Here's everything happening in this week's Sea of Thieves Forsaken Shores update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 September 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Shrouded Spoils''\n| 28 November 2018\n| ''Shrouded Spoils'' introduced [[fog]] into the game. The update also changed the AI behavior of both the kraken and the megalodon, and altered some of the existing gameplay systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-28-sea-of-thieves-big-shrouded-spoils-update-is-here-and-the-waters-never-been-deadlier|title=Sea of Thieves' big Shrouded Spoils update is here, and the water's never been deadlier|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Anniversary''\n| 30 April 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/111488/what-time-does-the-sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-start|title=What time does the Sea of Thieves Anniversary Update start?|first=Sam|last=Chandler|work=[[Shacknews]]|date=30 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| The ''Anniversary'' update introduced a separate player-versus-player (PvP) competitive multiplayer mode named ''Arena'', the first narrative-based Tall Tales campaign named ''Shores of Gold'' which consists of nine chapters, and the ''Hunter's Call'', which added fishing, cooking and hunting into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update/|title=Sea of Thieves' anniversary update finally makes the game reach its full potential|first=Samuel|last=Roberts|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=10 April 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Black Powder Staches''\n| 17 July 2019\n| ''Black Power Staches'' includes a series of missions that task players to collect gunpowder barrels and then sold them to various factions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-black-powder-stashes-update-is-live/|title=Sea of Thieves' Black Powder Stashes update is live|first=Christopher|last=Livington|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Dark Relics''\n| 15 August 2019\n| ''Dark Relics'' introduces new voyages, cosmetic items, new commentations, and rowboats mounted with [[harpoon gun]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-dark-relics-update-is-here-with-new-voyages/|title=Sea of Thieves' Dark Relics update is here with new voyages|first=Jordan|last=Gerblick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=15 August 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Smuggler's Fortune''\n| 11 September 2019\n| The update introduces Pirate Emporium, a new store that supports [[microtransaction]]s. A new type of currency named \"Ancient Coins\" can be purchased from Xbox store, though they can also be earned in the game. Players can also buy [[monkey]]s and [[parrot]]s as pets from Pirate Emporium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/11/20860753/sea-of-thieves-smugglers-fortune-update-pets|title=Sea of Thieves\u2019 Smuggler\u2019s Fortune update is now live, and it adds pets|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=11 September 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Fort of the Damned''\n| 16 October 2019\n| ''Fort of the Damned'' introduced several [[Halloween]]-themed cosmetics, a new skeleton font, and a new type of enemy named Shadow Skeletons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-gets-spooky-with-new-fort-of-the-da/1100-6470608/|title=Sea Of Thieves Gets Spooky With New Fort Of The Damned Update|first=Jordan|last=Ramee|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''The Seabound Soul''\n| 20 November 2019\n| ''The Seabound Soul'' introduced fire into the game with the fiery cannonball and a new Tall Tales which sees players partnering with adventurer Sir Arthur Pendragon as they embarck on a journey to seek a \"feared ship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-the-seabound-soul-update-now-live/1100-6471606/|title=Sea Of Thieves' The Seabound Soul Update Now Live|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Festival of Giving''\n| 11 December 2019\n| ''Festival of Giving'' introduced several [[Christmas]]-themed cosmetic items and a mission that task the players to assist Stitcher Jim to collect a shipment of gifts that was lost to the sea. A new tutorial mode named Maiden Voyage was also added into the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-holiday-event-adds-gift-seeker-voyages-and-tutorial-mode/|title=Sea of Thieves' holiday event adds Gift Seeker Voyages and tutorial mode|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=11 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Legends of the Sea''\n| 15 January 2020\n| ''Legends of the Sea'' celebrated the game's most notable players by tasking players to embarck on a quest to seek various easter eggs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/sea-of-thieves/legends-of-the-sea-release-date|title=Sea of Thieves: Legends of the Sea makes you part of the lore|first=Dustin|last=Bailey|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Crews of Rage''\n| 19 February 2020\n| ''Crews of Rage'' brought players back to Devil's Roar where they need to complete Bounty Voyages, which involves the acquisition of a new chest named the Chest of Rage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2020/02/19/crews-of-rage-sea-of-thieves-free-update-released/|title=The latest free update to Sea of Thieves is Crews of Rage|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|work=[[VG 247]]|date=19 February 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Heart of Fire''\n| 11 March 2020\n| ''Heart of Fire'' introduced the chain-shot and the blunderbomb, a throwable explosive, and included more Tall Tales missions which continue the story started in ''The Seabound Soul''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-04-sea-of-thieves-enters-the-trap-laden-heart-of-fire-in-next-weeks-big-update|title=Sea of Thieves enters the trap-laden Heart of Fire in next week's big update|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' saw frequent collaborations with other Microsoft franchises. The Bird and Bear Figurehead, based on Rare's own ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]'' series, was released in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/07/05/sea-of-thieves-new-item-is-a-lovely-banjo-kazooie-reference|title=Sea of Thieves: New Item Is a Lovely Banjo-Kazooie Reference|first=Alex|last=Gilyadov|work=[[IGN]]|date=7 May 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Ships based on the ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' series and the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise were released in June and November 2019 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/06/10/halo-spartan-ship-set-announced-for-sea-of-thieves-e3-2019|title=Halo Spartan Ship Set Announced for Sea of Thieves - E3 2019|first=Colin|last=Stevens|work=[[IGN]]|date=10 June 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-is-giving-away-a-gears-of-war-inspired-ship-set-for-a-week/|title=Sea of Thieves is giving away a Gears of War-inspired ship set for a week|first=Andy|last=Chalk|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Rare also expanded ''Sea of Thieves'' to other mediums. It have partnered with [[Mongoose Publishing]] to release a [[tabletop role-playing game|tabletop]] game titled ''Sea of Thieves Roleplaying Game'' in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-05-31-theres-a-sea-of-thieves-tabletop-rpg-on-the-way|title=There's a Sea of Thieves tabletop RPG on the way|first=Matt|last=Wales|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Comics]] debuted a comic series in March 2018, with [[Jeremy Whitley]] being the writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-comic-series-announced-check-out-so/1100-6455724/|title=Sea Of Thieves Comic Series Announced, Check Out Some Art|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=18 December 2017|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> [[Titan Books]] also worked with Rare to publish an art-book named ''Tales from the Sea of Thieves''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/xbox/2018/3/20/17140292/sea-of-thieves-lore-artbook-preview-tales-from-the-sea-of-thieves-book|title=Tales From the Sea of Thieves is a deep dive into a pirate lore ocean|first=Susana|last=Polo|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 66/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><br>(XONE) 69/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/sea-of-thieves |title=Sea of Thieves for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 6.5/10<ref name=\"DestructRev\">{{cite web |last=Devore |first=Jordan |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-sea-of-thieves-495603.phtml |title=Review: Sea of Thieves |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| EuroG = Recommended<ref name=\"EuroGRev\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-27-sea-of-thieves-review|title=Sea of Thieves review|first=Christian|last=Donlan|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=27 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"GIRev\">{{cite web |last=Hilliard |first=Kyle |date=23 March 2018 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/sea_of_thieves/b/xboxone/archive/2018/03/23/game-informer-sea-of-thieves-xbox-one-review.aspx |title=Fun In A Shallow Pool - Sea of Thieves - Xbox One |work=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web |last=Tamburro |first=Paul |date=26 March 2018 |url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/377727-sea-of-thieves-review-rarely-exciting-xbox-one |title=Sea of Thieves Review \u2013 Rarely Exciting (Xbox One) |publisher=[[Game Revolution]] |accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6/10<ref name=\"GSpotRev\">{{cite web |last=Brown |first=Peter |date=27 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/sea-of-thieves-review-set-sail-with-trepidation/1900-6416887/ |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadarRev\">{{cite web |last=Loveridge |first=Sam |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/sea-of-thieves-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review: Doesn\u2019t have the (sea)legs for longevity |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n| IGN = 7.0/10<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web |last=Tyrell |first=Brandin |date=27 March 2018 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/sea-of-thieves-review |title=Sea of Thieves Review |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=27 March 2018}}</ref>\n| Poly = 6.5/10<ref name=\"Poly\">{{cite web |last=Frushtick |first=Russ |date=22 March 2018 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17151248/sea-of-thieves-review-xbox-one-pc |title=Sea of Thieves review |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 72/100<ref name=\"PCGRev\">{{cite magazine |last=Wilde |first=Tyler |date=23 March 2018 |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/sea-of-thieves-pc-review/ |title=Sea of Thieves review |magazine=[[PC Gamer]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Sea of Thieves'' received \"mixed or average\" reviews from critics, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/> Most critics agreed that the game has potential and a good foundation but lamented that the game suffered from a lack of content and doubted Rare's decision to release ''Sea of Thieves'' as a full-priced game.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"DestructRev\"/><ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/><ref name=\"Poly\"/> The game's graphics and the [[game physics]] for the sea also received acclaim from critics.<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> \n\nThe multiplayer portion of the game received acclaim. Jordan Devore from ''[[Destructoid]]'' noted that with a full crew, the game could get chaotic and situations could turn volatile very quickly. He added that cooperation with strangers can also be deeply satisfying and added that these moments can create unforgettable experiences for players.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Peter Brown from ''[[GameSpot]]'' also enjoyed coordinating with other players or simply goofing around, though he remarked that some players were [[trolling]] others and caused the experience to become frustrating.<ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/> Jeff Grubb from ''[[VentureBeat]]'' also enjoyed the game, saying that playing with strangers often created numerous hilarious moments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/03/20/sea-of-thieves-is-mesmerizing-and-hilarious/|title=Sea of Thieves is mesmerizing and hilarious|first=Jeff|last=Grubb|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Kyle Hilliard from ''[[Game Informer]]'' stated that each session \"results in a story\" due to the emergent gameplay, and praised Rare for successfully creating an excellent \"pirate simulator\" and \"manufacturing a digital playground that is fun to explore\".<ref name=\"GIRev\"/>  Sam Loveridge from ''[[GamesRadar]]'' likewise commented that the game is \"an anecdote generator at its very best\" due to its emergent storytelling.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Brandin Tyrrel from ''[[IGN]]'' stated that \"''Sea of Thieves'' works well when treated like a [[chat room]] or a [[party game]], where it serves as catalyst for having a good time with the people you\u2019re with\".<ref name=\"IGN\"/>\n\nThe gameplay received generally negative reviews. Devore felt that the quests were repetitive and that the world did not have a lot of interesting things to do.<ref name=\"DestructRev\"/> Paul Tamburro from ''[[Game Revolution]]'' agreed, remarking that the quests had little variety and did not allow room for creativity. While he praised the huge [[sandbox game|sandbox]], he felt that there were not enough secrets or stories players can discover in the world.<ref name=\"GameRev\"/> Loverdige called the voyages \"elaborated [[fetch quest]]s. He lamented that there were no option to turn off PvP in the game and that they cannot customize their own characters.<ref name=\"GRadarRev\"/> Russ Frushtick from ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' remarked that misbehaving players can make the experience frustrating because PvP can never be disabled. However, he remarked that the game offered no incentive for players who wanted to engage in PvP combat.<ref name=\"Poly\"/> Hilliard felt that the game did not have enough content to keep players engaged, and remarked that the combat felt bland. Many critics commented that players would not be motivated to complete quests because only cosmetic items are unlocked.<ref name=\"GIRev\"/><ref name=\"GameRev\"/><ref name=\"GSpotRev\"/><ref name=\"IGN\"/> Tyrrel praised the ship combat, though he felt that the respawn system was too forgiving.<ref name=\"IGN\"/> Christian Donlan from ''[[Eurogamer]]'' likewise called the ship combat \"thrilling\" and the general combat \"crunchy, pleasantly basic\".<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> Tyler Wilde from ''[[PC Gamer]]'' liked exploring the shipwrecks for evoking a sense of discovery, though he commented that he wished more emergent events would happen in the ocean.<ref name=\"PCGRev\"/> Solo play received mixed opinions. Some critics thought that it was more difficult,<ref name=\"polysolo\"/> boring,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-is-no-fun-by-yourself-1823934837|title=Sea Of Thieves Is No Fun By Yourself|first=Mike|last=Fahey|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and maddening,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/03/21/sea-of-thieves-solo-play/|title=Sea of Thieves solo is maddening and brutal - as it should be|first=Alec|last=Meer|work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while some remarked that it is entertaining,<ref name=\"EuroGRev\"/> satisfying,<ref name=\"rpsoslo\"/> and relaxing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-02-01-why-i-love-sailing-alone-in-sea-of-thieves|title=Why I love sailing alone in Sea of Thieves|first=Robert|last=Purchese|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"polysolo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/22/17150830/playing-sea-of-thieves-solo-experience|title=The case for sailing solo in Sea of Thieves|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing a year of updates, the game received a more positive reception from critics. Following the ''Anniversary'' update, ''IGN'' stated that players should give the game a second chance and that it was the \"perfect time\" for players to return to the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/05/13/why-now-is-a-great-time-to-return-to-sea-of-thieves|title=Why Now Is a Great Time to Return to Sea of Thieves|first=Mark|last=Merlinda|work=[[IGN]]|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Nicole Carpenter from ''Polygon'' praised the post-launch updates for making the title more \"curated\" with more structure and direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/5/9/18538173/sea-of-thieves-anniversary-update-review-xbox-pc|title=Sea of Thieves 2019 review: A sea change|first=Nicole|last=Carpenter|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> David Jagneaux from ''IGN'', in his re-review of the game in 2020, praised the Tall Tales and its riddles, which he described as \"brain teasers that really challenge [player's] detective skills\". In his summary, he wrote that the game is a \"pirate fantasy sandbox with an enormous amount of things to do, made unpredictable and exciting by the addition of other players\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-review-2020|title=Sea of Thieves (2020) review|first=David|last=Jagneaux|work=[[IGN]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> ''[[PC Gamer]]'' named ''Sea of Thieves'' the Best Ongoing Game of 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/best-ongoing-game-2019-sea-of-thieves/|title=Best Ongoing Game 2019: Sea of Thieves|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=19 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> while Gameindustry.biz declared the title one of their [[Game of the Year|Games of the Year]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2019-12-15-game-of-the-year-2019-sea-of-thieves|title=Games of the Year 2019: Sea of Thieves|first=Christopher|last=Dring|work=Gameindustry.biz|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Sales===\n''Sea of Thieves'' was a commercial success. The title attracted more than 1 million players two days after it has released,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-seeing-unprecedented-demand-passes-/1100-6457743/|title=Sea Of Thieves Seeing \"Unprecedented\" Demand, Passes 1 Million Players|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> It was the best-selling retail game in the UK in its week of release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-03-26-sea-of-thieves-lands-uk-chart-number-one|title=Sea of Thieves lands UK chart number one|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=26 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> and it became the second best-selling game in the US in March 2018, only behind ''[[Far Cry 5]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/04/25/far-cry-5-sea-of-thieves-march-npd/|title=Far Cry 5 and Sea of Thieves best-selling games in US during March, according to NPD|first=James|last=Billcliffe|work=[[VG 247]]|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> On 28 March 2018, Microsoft declared the game as the fast-selling new IP released for the Xbox One.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-microsofts-fastest-selling-new-i/1100-6457750/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Microsoft's Fastest-Selling New IP On Xbox One|first=Kevin|last=Knezevic|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-11-quantum-break-uks-best-selling-boxed-game |title=Quantum Break UK's best-selling boxed game |first=Wesley |last=Yin-Poole |work=[[Eurogamer]] |date=11 April 2016 |accessdate=11 April 2016}}</ref> Rare attributed the game's success to the title releasing for Xbox Game Pass subscribers at launch, which enabled the game to achieved Rare's sales target for three months in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-06-18-sea-of-thieves-hit-three-month-target-in-a-single-day|title=Sea of Thieves hit three month target in a single day|first=Matthew|last= Handrahan|work=[[Gameindustry.biz]]|date=18 June 2016|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Game Pass contributed to half of the sales of ''Sea of Thieves'',<ref name=\"second launch\"/> though Microsoft added that the game sold well without counting the Game Pass sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/315909/Microsoft_says_Sea_of_Thieves_sold_well_even_without_counting_Game_Pass_copies.php|title=Microsoft says Sea of Thieves sold well, even without counting Game Pass copies|first=Alissa|last=McAloon|work=[[Gamasutra]]|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The game passed five million players in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-08-01-sea-of-thieves-sloops-past-5m-players|title=Sea of Thieves passes 5m players|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In January 2020, Microsoft declared the game the most successful IP it has released in the generation, with the game amassing more than 10 million players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/sea-of-thieves-is-now-xboxs-most-successful-new-ip/1100-6472598/|title=Sea Of Thieves Is Now Xbox's \"Most Successful\" New IP Of The Generation|first=Jeremy|last=Winslow|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> In addition to good sales, ''Sea of Thieves'' was also popular with viewers, with the title being ranked as one of the most watched titles on Twitch in January 2019 following the ''Shrouded Spoils'' update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/sea-of-thieves-has-unexpectedly-become-one-of-twitchs-b-1831997645|title=Sea Of Thieves Has Unexpectedly Become One Of Twitch's Biggest Games|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=23 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/1/22/18193421/sea-of-thieves-twitch-ninja-dr-disrespect-summit1g|title=Sea of Thieves is enjoying a resurgence on Twitch|first=Cass|last=Marshall|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2016\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamecriticsawards.com/2016nominees.html|title=Game Critics Awards: Best of E3 2016 (2016 Nominees)|publisher=[[Game Critics Awards]]|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Original Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Gamescom]] 2016\n| Best Xbox One Game\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamelibrarian.com/best-of-gamescom-2016-winners-selected-by-gamescom-committee/|title=Best of Gamescom 2016 Winners Selected by Gamescom Committee|publisher=The Video Game Librarian|date=19 August 2016|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Social/Online Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Multiplayer Game\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| s